INSERT INTO `cms_content` VALUES ('1','8T7H7D57juXfgTmtA3VmwfXJvP7v5ADS',2,'text/html','',0,'sadfsdafdsa','2017-07-03 16:43:34','2017-07-03 16:43:34'),('10','nUKeAeU6xiwFCMtNMr58JoqtEyFgUMie',2,'text/html','',1,'dsafdsafdsfdsa','2017-07-03 17:04:32','2017-07-03 17:04:32'),('100','HMRaJz3US3FKMWUer42TB28fjveN6wFX',2,'text/html','',2,'This code is asking for the file “file_from_server.txt” from http://somebody.com.   \nWe specify how to retrieve that file with the first parameter to xhttp.open.\nIn this case we use GET because we aren’t sending any additional data. \nHowever, if we wanted to send some other binary data along with the request, we\'d use either POST or PUT.   \nI\'ll be sure to go into more detail with this later.\nThe second argument tells the browser what file to look for.   \nAnd the final parameter tells the browser to wait until a response is received from the server before moving on to the next set of instructions.  \nIf we change this parameter to true, the browser will create another thread and do all of the sending and receiving in the background.\nThis thread creation allows the browser to engage in what\'s known as <i>asynchronous communication</i>, where the client and server can communicate when resources are available.','2017-07-25 20:55:23','2017-07-25 20:55:23'),('101','HMRaJz3US3FKMWUer42TB28fjveN6wFX',2,'text/html','',3,'Now the key takeaway here (and one of the reasons I\'m explaining all of this) is that file_from_server.txt could be just about <i>anything</i>.  \nOften, it could be a file, but it could simply be an endpoint for uploading new files.\nIt might simply be a page stub that creates new files on receipt of some code from the user.\nEither way, though, it\'s the beginning of an API---the standard for most modern web applications today.\nWith proper backend architecture, an application can share most of its data with another party through the use of simple HTTP requests.   ','2017-07-25 20:56:03','2017-07-25 20:56:03'),('102','L3EaR87MSaHnKIWsUkKrhafJyirQIeBe',2,'text/html','',0,'Just started playing with Laravel after a long time of not really touching PHP.  To get it running wasn\'t as straight-forward as I hoped,  so I\'ve written a little set of instructions to help me remember how to get it going in the future.  This little guide is only for Cygwin right now, as I have yet to do this on a real Unix box.','2017-07-26 14:57:02','2017-07-26 14:57:02'),('103','L3EaR87MSaHnKIWsUkKrhafJyirQIeBe',2,'text/html','',1,'If you have not already done so, download \n<a href=\"\">apt-cyg</a>.  \nIt\'s an indispensable tool for your Cygwin toolkit and makes life much easier.\nThe script is located on Github, and you probably won\'t find a package for it when running setup.exe. \nHowever, it is a quick and easy install via the command-line. \nYou can copy and paste the following into your terminal:\n<pre>\nlynx -source rawgit.com/transcode-open/apt-cyg/master/apt-cyg > apt-cyg\ninstall apt-cyg /bin\n</pre>','2017-07-26 15:14:50','2017-07-26 15:14:50'),('104','L3EaR87MSaHnKIWsUkKrhafJyirQIeBe',2,'text/html','',2,'You\'ll also want to upgrade Cygwin so you have the newest versions of all software.   \nYou will need to run setup.exe for this, unfortunately, but newer versions of Cygwin highlight all that you need to get current.','2017-07-26 15:15:00','2017-07-26 15:15:00'),('105','L3EaR87MSaHnKIWsUkKrhafJyirQIeBe',2,'text/html','',3,'Laravel needs a fair bit to get running on a vanilla system.  \nAs stated on the website, a basic installation of Laravel depends on Composer, OpenSSL, PDO, MBString, Tokenizer and XML .\nComposer is used to manage the project\'s dependencies, but if you have not done this in a while, you\'ll find that there are more packages than you bargainzed for.','2017-07-26 15:15:06','2017-07-26 15:15:06'),('106','L3EaR87MSaHnKIWsUkKrhafJyirQIeBe',2,'text/html','',4,'To PHP set up the way we need it, try the following:','2017-07-26 15:15:11','2017-07-26 15:15:11'),('107','L3EaR87MSaHnKIWsUkKrhafJyirQIeBe',2,'text/html','',5,'<pre>\napt-cyg install php php-mbstring, php-pdo_*, php_iconv, php-tokenizer, php-xmlreader, php-xmlwriter, php-zlib, php-zip\n</pre>','2017-07-26 15:15:14','2017-07-26 15:15:14'),('108','L3EaR87MSaHnKIWsUkKrhafJyirQIeBe',2,'text/html','',6,'That should handle all of the dependencies needed to make Laravel not complain.','2017-07-26 15:15:26','2017-07-26 15:15:26'),('109','L3EaR87MSaHnKIWsUkKrhafJyirQIeBe',2,'text/html','',7,'The next step is Composer.   I must say, this could probably be much cleaner and I\'m not sure why a simple shell script is not shipped with this tool.  Anyway, the commands to get it running are something like:','2017-07-26 15:15:32','2017-07-26 15:15:32'),('11','nUKeAeU6xiwFCMtNMr58JoqtEyFgUMie',4,'image/jpeg','',2,'n4rn1EFdZJaKAJLnW6ry164ZxiW64MtE.jpg','2017-07-03 17:04:35','2017-07-03 17:04:35'),('110','L3EaR87MSaHnKIWsUkKrhafJyirQIeBe',2,'text/html','',8,'<pre>\n#!/bin/sh\nEXPECTED_SIGNATURE=$(wget -q -O - https://composer.github.io/installer.sig)\nphp -r \"copy(\'https://getcomposer.org/installer\', \'composer-setup.php\');\"\nACTUAL_SIGNATURE=$(php -r \"echo hash_file(\'SHA384\', \'composer-setup.php\');\")\n\nif [ \"$EXPECTED_SIGNATURE\" != \"$ACTUAL_SIGNATURE\" ]\nthen\n    >&2 echo \'ERROR: Invalid installer signature\'\n    rm composer-setup.php\n    exit 1\nfi\n\nphp composer-setup.php --quiet\nRESULT=$?\nrm composer-setup.php\nexit $RESULT\n</pre>','2017-07-26 15:15:38','2017-07-26 15:15:38'),('111','L3EaR87MSaHnKIWsUkKrhafJyirQIeBe',2,'text/html','',9,'Per Composer\'s site, these commands will always give you the newest version.\nIf you do run into any errors, however, visit <a href=\"https://getcomposer.org/download/\">Composer\'s website</a> for the most up-to-date instructions.','2017-07-26 15:15:45','2017-07-26 15:15:45'),('112','L3EaR87MSaHnKIWsUkKrhafJyirQIeBe',2,'text/html','',10,'Now, Cygwin still has another step to get rolling.   The Composer setup script does <i>not</i> install a copy of Composer globally.   So you will have to roll your own link.','2017-07-26 15:15:57','2017-07-26 15:15:57'),('113','L3EaR87MSaHnKIWsUkKrhafJyirQIeBe',2,'text/html','',11,'<pre>\n[ -f composer.phar ] && { mv composer.phar /usr/local/bin/composer; }\ncomposer global require \"laravel/installer\"\nln -s $HOME/.composer/vendor/bin/laravel /usr/local/bin/\nlaravel 2>|grep \'laravel\' #Should show output...\n</pre>\n','2017-07-26 15:16:03','2017-07-26 15:16:03'),('114','L3EaR87MSaHnKIWsUkKrhafJyirQIeBe',2,'text/html','',12,'So, provided that you were able to get here with no issues, you should have a nice Laravel installation ready to roll.  And you too, can roll out some fancy new PHP websites.','2017-07-26 15:16:42','2017-07-26 15:16:42'),('115','L3EaR87MSaHnKIWsUkKrhafJyirQIeBe',2,'text/html','',13,'Hope this helps!','2017-07-26 15:16:48','2017-07-26 15:16:48'),('116','zkDqr7NCTWkfDkUH1BOduqfvsgiHSltU',2,'text/html','',0,'git server (5)\n	A command tells it to run if I remember correctly...\n	\n	The following command starts the server:\n		git instaweb --httpd=<your httpd daemon of choice>\n		\n	Do you want to look through the commit logs?:\n		paste shots\n		or\n		git ...\n		\n	Add a description \n		That way everybody knows what to do...\n		\n	Managing things to ignore...\n		http://stackoverflow.com/jobs/135989/c-plus-plus-developer-game-integration-tobii-ab?offset=9&q=Objective+C\n	Look at all commits from a certain user?\n		...\n		\n	Git\n		quick team setup\n			Need a user installed / configured\n			Each person needs a remote\n			Each person needs SSH keys or some other authentication\n	\n	Here are some easy ways to run this:\n	http://stackoverflow.com/questions/51619/how-to-setup-git-bare-http-available-repository-on-iis-machine','2017-07-28 14:27:54','2017-07-28 14:27:54'),('117','zkDqr7NCTWkfDkUH1BOduqfvsgiHSltU',2,'text/html','',1,'Configure a Git project directory\n		?','2017-07-28 14:27:59','2017-07-28 14:27:59'),('118','mLz8O3EhMsQjO2gmEJInOLxDS4xDrfqF',2,'text/html','',0,'Nothing should be said about anything ever again...','2017-07-28 14:43:38','2017-07-28 14:43:38'),('119','mLz8O3EhMsQjO2gmEJInOLxDS4xDrfqF',4,'image/jpeg','',1,'LmQ0Yi5Uiv6y1ZULYEvS7NZSyVVIquKt.jpg','2017-07-28 14:44:09','2017-07-28 14:44:09'),('12','B4bcFCre2yzcdvnhmmUdoX6GrTg1VNVM',2,'text/html','',0,'sadfsdaf','2017-07-03 17:05:15','2017-07-03 17:05:15'),('120','mLz8O3EhMsQjO2gmEJInOLxDS4xDrfqF',2,'text/html','',2,'In the meantime, at least we\'ve got this cool car to look at...','2017-07-28 14:44:19','2017-07-28 14:44:19'),('121','dcO6RbhD1kHVlMoY8MuwrIU3rEB1wzuS',2,'text/html','',0,'asdfasdf','2017-07-28 14:47:19','2017-07-28 14:47:19'),('122','rzDw57Ij61G4hAyZXmccSftzbN0ivGx4',2,'text/html','',0,'sdafasdfasdf','2017-07-28 14:49:02','2017-07-28 14:49:02'),('123','ymgxK0FX6tJOsV0W0EyAuq3TMo2FjBw0',2,'text/html','',0,'asdfasdfasdf','2017-07-28 14:49:55','2017-07-28 14:49:55'),('124','rcQ8HkE77VZcmb1SqJcgjFAwXuvEjJ6W',2,'text/html','',0,'asdfasdf','2017-07-28 14:50:40','2017-07-28 14:50:40'),('125','bSZmIV6sagnHvVOEDsuhYyQchNY724lk',2,'text/html','',0,'asdfasdfsd','2017-07-28 14:51:38','2017-07-28 14:51:38'),('126','DNatxIzxqidszDq1QBctgcKmHNbjgywy',2,'text/html','',0,'Yaassssss queen bitch.  Shut your faggotronic ass up...','2017-07-28 14:53:17','2017-07-28 14:53:17'),('127','75Cjc4YmXa5fSl8LkYn7k8XWKSqoGt16',2,'text/html','',0,'There is little for you to worry about my friend.','2017-07-28 14:54:46','2017-07-28 14:54:46'),('128','75Cjc4YmXa5fSl8LkYn7k8XWKSqoGt16',2,'text/html','',1,'Eww...','2017-07-28 14:54:49','2017-07-28 14:54:49'),('129','Fhs0cdfaoKtgcSLXEYMFVARCqJnW4jS8',2,'text/html','',0,'<h2>Make a Copy of the Database</h2>','2017-07-28 15:20:29','2017-07-28 15:20:29'),('13','ecFCHtMNBk6zzqEdwrj8tccvdlQ14xK2',2,'text/html','',0,'This will be the first time I\'ve written something new in a while.','2017-07-03 17:22:54','2017-07-03 17:22:54'),('130','Fhs0cdfaoKtgcSLXEYMFVARCqJnW4jS8',2,'text/html','',1,'<pre>\nshell> mysqldump db1 > dump.sql\nshell> mysqladmin create db2\nshell> mysql db2 < dump.sql\n</pre>','2017-07-28 15:20:40','2017-07-28 15:20:40'),('131','Fs5ZSThc8oaBUjmdfSz26AhBUYZKgTm7',2,'text/html','',0,'HTML color pickers are everywhere, but it\'s a little rare to see one that lets you save palettes. ','2017-07-28 15:21:55','2017-07-28 15:21:55'),('132','Fs5ZSThc8oaBUjmdfSz26AhBUYZKgTm7',2,'text/html','',1,'<pre>\n/default\n		two tiles - top = 6 squares, bottom = a whole bunch of other stuff\n		+ -------------------+--------------------+------------------ + \n		+                    +                    +                   + \n		+    <color>         +                    +                   + \n		+                    +                    +                   + \n		+ -------------------+--------------------+------------------ + \n		+                    +                    +                   + \n		+                    +                    +                   + \n		+                    +                    +                   + 		\n		+ -------------------+--------------------+------------------ +  \n		+ --------------------------- + + --------------------------- + \n		+                             + +                             + \n		+      <picker>               + + --------------------------- + \n		+                             + +                             + \n		+                             + + --------------------------- + \n		+                             + +                             + \n		+                             + + --------------------------- +\n		+                             + +                             + \n		+ --------------------------- + + --------------------------- + \n		\n		everything is flexbox\n			.main { flex }\n			.oneSixth { ?? }\n			\n			.oneHalf { ?? }\n			.oneHalf {\n				.li?\n			}\n	/save\n	\n	be able to save a palette and recall it (and name it)\n	this should take me 30 minutes to do...\n		even without a framework...\n	\n	this is a great demonstration\n	and good for let\'s rebuild or something...\n</pre>','2017-07-28 15:22:07','2017-07-28 15:22:07'),('133','Mtx6wQ0FikyDk6mI2G5cO2SG8dNiTnku',2,'text/html','',0,'learn ruby and document it here...','2017-07-28 15:38:51','2017-07-28 15:38:51'),('134','TtbcNywiE7hCXzrkA1MvFUocDXkF7n3m',4,'image/jpeg','',0,'GdElESLCGu56zVtTgmnLsZf8Beh6oFB7.jpg','2017-08-11 19:23:05','2017-08-11 19:23:05'),('135','HgYJwRLEkxjm0wyzxsJ5tuCBag6ioOFf',4,'image/jpeg','',0,'wxn5Ejo7GEvoSslhU8sLwIseVChUajbW.jpg','2017-08-21 14:29:39','2017-08-21 14:29:39'),('136','HgYJwRLEkxjm0wyzxsJ5tuCBag6ioOFf',2,'text/html','',1,'Type in your paragraph here...','2017-08-21 14:29:43','2017-08-21 14:29:43'),('137','JE1Q6BoDjhhjgmwrFTmWCbGORhCQmLLS',2,'text/html','',0,'If you ever need to make a quick functional checklist and don\'t want to use a web-based tool, try Vim.  I used Vim\'s folding feature when trying to summarize a few projects I\'ve got going on currently.\n\n','2017-09-07 12:27:59','2017-09-07 12:27:59'),('138','JE1Q6BoDjhhjgmwrFTmWCbGORhCQmLLS',2,'text/html','',1,'To get basic folds working on Vim, you\'ll need to tell Vim that you want enable folding.   If you want to enable the feature on one file, the following would do the trick.\n','2017-09-07 12:29:10','2017-09-07 12:29:10'),('139','JE1Q6BoDjhhjgmwrFTmWCbGORhCQmLLS',2,'text/html','',2,'<pre>\n# vim: foldmethod=indent\n</pre>\n','2017-09-07 12:29:28','2017-09-07 12:29:28'),('14','ecFCHtMNBk6zzqEdwrj8tccvdlQ14xK2',4,'image/jpeg','',1,'mRM3NSJKdiuTEt8nsqqjgcOhnnKr7SLg.jpg','2017-07-03 17:22:59','2017-07-03 17:22:59'),('140','JE1Q6BoDjhhjgmwrFTmWCbGORhCQmLLS',2,'text/html','',3,'Now, let\'s break that down. \nThe hashtag is just a comment that works for most programming languages. I needed folding on a text file, so this wasn\'t really necessary.  If you wanted to add folds to a Javascript or C file, you\'d want to use a single line comment that would make sense to either of those languages.','2017-09-07 12:31:15','2017-09-07 12:31:15'),('141','JE1Q6BoDjhhjgmwrFTmWCbGORhCQmLLS',2,'text/html','',4,'The term \'vim:\' is (presumably) telling Vim that there is a special way to handle this particular file.','2017-09-07 12:32:06','2017-09-07 12:32:06'),('142','JE1Q6BoDjhhjgmwrFTmWCbGORhCQmLLS',2,'text/html','',5,'Finally, \'foldmethod=indent\' tells Vim to fold on all indents.  Since this was a text file, I was easily able ','2017-09-07 12:33:01','2017-09-07 12:33:01'),('143','JE1Q6BoDjhhjgmwrFTmWCbGORhCQmLLS',2,'text/html','',6,'Finally, \'foldmethod=indent\' tells Vim to fold on all indents.  Since this was a text file, I was able to simply indent to make a new category (or subcategory).  For folding within a programming language, a better method will probably be desired.','2017-09-07 12:34:45','2017-09-07 12:34:45'),('144','JE1Q6BoDjhhjgmwrFTmWCbGORhCQmLLS',2,'text/html','',7,'Per Vim\'s \':help\' command, there are six possible fold methods.  They are as follows (with very light paraphrasing):\n<ul>\n<li>manual - manually define your folds</li>\n<li>indent - more indents mean higher fold levels</li>\n<li>expr - use an expression (in VimScript) to define folds</li>\n<li>syntax - folds defined by syntax highlighting</li>\n<li>diff - folds for unchanged text</li>\n<li>marker - folds are defined by markers in the text (usually comments)</li>\n</ul>','2017-09-07 12:37:39','2017-09-07 12:37:39'),('145','JE1Q6BoDjhhjgmwrFTmWCbGORhCQmLLS',2,'text/html','',8,'So unfortunately, I won\'t be covering folding in great depth here.  I don\'t really find it useful for most programming languages.  I figured I\'d share what I came up with today, though, for anyone who needs to quickly sort out some lists and already knows their way around a Vim window.','2017-09-07 12:39:29','2017-09-07 12:39:29'),('146','JE1Q6BoDjhhjgmwrFTmWCbGORhCQmLLS',2,'text/html','',9,'Thanks for reading!','2017-09-07 12:39:36','2017-09-07 12:39:36'),('147','iDb3X1kwuSbFRy8hczWvQWg40a2vXnCm',2,'text/html','',0,'Next time you\'re having some trouble keeping binary files out of your version control tree, try a little scripting magic to help you out.\n<pre>\ngit status | grep \'modified:\' | awk \'{ print $2 }\'\n</pre>\nThis will keep your source tree only tracking what you\'ve told it to track, lest you forgot to add a .gitignore file.  Or maybe you have needs that prevent you from using one.  Hope this helps someone.','2017-09-08 22:08:46','2017-09-08 22:08:46'),('148','l4KXtigKAhFy8uZkCVnANatOwqSQi0Tr',2,'text/html','',0,'I\'m visiting San Francisco at the moment and just broke a really crucial rule.  I bought a Macbook Pro.  Even though I\'ve needed one for quite a while (and am somewhat disliking some stupid things about it, such as not being able to connect to the wireless in some cafes--but having no trouble doing the same with my Arch Linux based Thinkpad x230), I\'ve decided to make what I think is a wise change.   Plus, I\'m probably gonna run Arch on it anyway.  Cheers!','2017-09-13 23:37:27','2017-09-13 23:37:27'),('149','fuU7QTxtYmkOwOk4YJtIKBnHqUJ5KTfa',2,'text/html','',0,'Today, my car died again.   This made me late for work (and subsequently unable to get there at all).   This also made me realize that it is time to make some big changes to go ahead and fix up my life.   I want to get far more serious about design and want to make others happy with the work I\'m doing.  I want to make 1 million before I\'m 32, but realize this means I\'ll have to work damned hard. ','2017-09-15 17:17:25','2017-09-15 17:17:25'),('15','ecFCHtMNBk6zzqEdwrj8tccvdlQ14xK2',2,'text/html','',2,'Ooh look, it\'s a picture of a little doggie!','2017-07-03 17:23:10','2017-07-03 17:23:10'),('150','I5dJSJgmOhKqn1mVKz22c0QGzeGnwgtl',2,'text/html','',0,'Let\'s get this right this time.','2017-09-15 17:17:57','2017-09-15 17:17:57'),('151','I5dJSJgmOhKqn1mVKz22c0QGzeGnwgtl',4,'image/jpeg','',1,'hQIcvoAWedYdjBc4sNA44HaFHfAnWr26.jpg','2017-09-15 17:25:34','2017-09-15 17:25:34'),('152','I5dJSJgmOhKqn1mVKz22c0QGzeGnwgtl',2,'text/html','',2,'Looks like it worked on the front end.  So now, let\'s submit and get it working on the backend.','2017-09-15 17:25:55','2017-09-15 17:25:55'),('153','4NKs01dRCTTiFf3Kro214LWRSQIJq5Aq',2,'text/html','',0,'It\'s been about a year and a half since I started working at North Carolina Central University.  They are a fairly medium sized HBCU located in the middle of Durham, North Carolina and have been around since 1909.  This is my first position in higher education and a lot of things were much different than working at a regular Fortune 500 company.  One thing, I did not see coming however, is using a language for server-side development that I had not touched before.   TL;DR Lucee is not really such a bad solution for developing your web applications today, especially if you are skilled in Java and do not want to deal with compilation. ','2017-09-18 21:21:29','2017-09-18 21:21:29'),('154','4NKs01dRCTTiFf3Kro214LWRSQIJq5Aq',2,'text/html','',1,'At NCCU, Lucee is the stack of choice for server-side application development.   I\'ll avoid any opinionated rants about the positives and negatives of that choice in this article, but instead attempt to layout an educated use case for anyone looking to deploy a website for a large organization.  To keep things fair and balanced, I\'ll lay down one negative and one positive.','2017-09-18 21:21:38','2017-09-18 21:21:38'),('155','4NKs01dRCTTiFf3Kro214LWRSQIJq5Aq',2,'text/html','',2,'<h3>+ <b><i>EVERYTHING</i></b> is built-in</h3>','2017-09-18 21:21:49','2017-09-18 21:21:49'),('156','4NKs01dRCTTiFf3Kro214LWRSQIJq5Aq',2,'text/html','',3,'As a web developer watching the ecosystem today, I cannot stress this point enough.  This is the single best thing about using Lucee.   I don\'t need Apache, nginx, PHP modules, junky Debian scripts, npm, babel, gradle or any of the myriad tools out there to get something running.  Working on Lucee sites has given me the advantage and freedom to just download a package, answer some questions and run the resultant script.  Here, let me show you how to get Lucee running on your system.\n','2017-09-18 21:21:55','2017-09-18 21:21:55'),('157','4NKs01dRCTTiFf3Kro214LWRSQIJq5Aq',2,'text/html','',4,'<pre>\nme $ wget http://cdn.lucee.org/lucee-5.2.3.035-pl0-linux-x64-installer.run\nme $ chmod +x lucee-5.2.3.035-pl0-linux-x64-installer.run\nme $ sudo ./lucee-5.2.3.035-pl0-linux-x64-installer.run\nme $ <answer some questions>...\n</pre>','2017-09-18 21:22:00','2017-09-18 21:22:00'),('158','4NKs01dRCTTiFf3Kro214LWRSQIJq5Aq',2,'text/html','',5,'Wow.  And that\'s the hard way.  You can also just use Lucee Express and hit ./startup.sh to get a server running. ','2017-09-18 21:22:07','2017-09-18 21:22:07'),('159','4NKs01dRCTTiFf3Kro214LWRSQIJq5Aq',2,'text/html','',6,'So I didn\'t need to download Java, because it comes bundled with it.  The package is maybe 200 MB, which I complained about quite a bit when first starting off.  But when I think of the madness that is installaing something like Laravel with probably close to half a gig of PHP packages, Javascript and Apache modules that I will probably never use again, I\'m consoled.','2017-09-18 21:22:17','2017-09-18 21:22:17'),('16','6uz1UBYY1WL0zQySeET7u6VhS18oo2dT',2,'text/html','',0,'here is  some post data...','2017-07-03 17:26:07','2017-07-03 17:26:07'),('160','4NKs01dRCTTiFf3Kro214LWRSQIJq5Aq',2,'text/html','',7,'<pre>\nme $ sudo apt-get install php composer php-[bla,bla,mcbla] # and a whole bunch of other stuff I can\'t remember right now\n</pre>','2017-09-18 21:22:24','2017-09-18 21:22:24'),('161','4NKs01dRCTTiFf3Kro214LWRSQIJq5Aq',2,'text/html','',8,'Most any authentication, hashing and salt methods are there.  Most database drivers just ship with it (curiously enough, SQLite is missing.  Why?).   Session management ships as well and supports multiple backends (file, database and memory).  A mail function and an LDAP function both exist.  And, if you\'re into that sort of thing, you get a pretty well polished GUI.  ','2017-09-18 21:22:34','2017-09-18 21:22:34'),('162','4NKs01dRCTTiFf3Kro214LWRSQIJq5Aq',2,'text/html','',9,'However, this brings me to my negative point.','2017-09-18 21:22:43','2017-09-18 21:22:43'),('163','4NKs01dRCTTiFf3Kro214LWRSQIJq5Aq',2,'text/html','',10,'<h3>- <b><i>EVERYTHING</i></b> besides a package manager...</h3>','2017-09-18 21:22:49','2017-09-18 21:22:49'),('164','4NKs01dRCTTiFf3Kro214LWRSQIJq5Aq',2,'text/html','',11,'Honestly, I probably shouldn\'t have given this one a negative, but one of the reasons for the growth of communities like npm and pypy is because of the ubiquity of the package management aspects.   Lucee has a meager community right now (when compared to the communities using node and brethren) and as such it is a bit difficult to find modern extensions for those times you really need them.   OAuth is one big thing I can think of that there is no gold standard for.  While an OAuth implementation is not that hard to bang out (I\'ve done in Lua before and that wasn\'t at all a bag of roses), it would be incredibly helpful to new users if basics like this already existed.  ','2017-09-18 21:22:56','2017-09-18 21:22:56'),('165','4NKs01dRCTTiFf3Kro214LWRSQIJq5Aq',2,'text/html','',12,'That said, there are some managers rolling around, but you have to download a lot of extra tooling to get started with it. (See <a href=https://www.ortussolutions.com/products/commandbox>CommandBox</a>.) Worse, I don\'t think the community is fully behind it yet.  There used to be RIAForge, but that has been abandoned and left for dead long ago.','2017-09-18 21:23:07','2017-09-18 21:23:07'),('166','4NKs01dRCTTiFf3Kro214LWRSQIJq5Aq',2,'text/html','',13,'<h3>+ CFML is god-awful, but nothing special is needed to do some templating</h3>','2017-09-18 21:23:16','2017-09-18 21:23:16'),('167','4NKs01dRCTTiFf3Kro214LWRSQIJq5Aq',2,'text/html','',14,'As web developers, it would be a bit ridiculous to say we don\'t need templating.\nIt would be even more ridiculous to use a framework that left templating as an afterthought.   Yes, the world has changed quite a bit since most languages came about, but pretty much all of them have kept up with this.','2017-09-18 21:23:22','2017-09-18 21:23:22'),('168','4NKs01dRCTTiFf3Kro214LWRSQIJq5Aq',2,'text/html','',15,'I absolutely <b>HATE</b> CFML.  (It might work for you, so that statement is pure opinion.  Try it for yourself.) However, I do like that it facilitates writing templates without a lot of fuss. ','2017-09-18 21:23:27','2017-09-18 21:23:27'),('169','4NKs01dRCTTiFf3Kro214LWRSQIJq5Aq',2,'text/html','',16,'Let\'s use Mustache as an example, the logic-less wunderkind of the template universe.   ','2017-09-18 21:23:31','2017-09-18 21:23:31'),('17','6uz1UBYY1WL0zQySeET7u6VhS18oo2dT',4,'image/jpeg','',1,'8U6wMjxN2hV3C21rzNwhY5aQt3S07Zwd.jpg','2017-07-03 17:26:11','2017-07-03 17:26:11'),('170','4NKs01dRCTTiFf3Kro214LWRSQIJq5Aq',2,'text/html','',17,'<h3>- CFML is god-awful.  Period.</h3>','2017-09-18 21:23:39','2017-09-18 21:23:39'),('171','4NKs01dRCTTiFf3Kro214LWRSQIJq5Aq',2,'text/html','',18,'<pre>\n<cfhttp bla=1>\n<cfquery name=\"etc\" datasource=\"yourmom\">\nSELECT * FROM no_fs_given \n</cfquery>\n<html>\n<cfset GreetingText=\"Hello, and welcome to this spiffy webpage.\">\n<cfset rounds=0>\n<p>\n</p>\n<table>\n<cfloop query=\"etc\">\n	<tr>\n		<td>etc.column1</td>\n		<td>etc.column2</td>\n		<td>etc.column3</td>\n	</tr>\n</cfloop>\n</table>\n</pre>','2017-09-18 21:23:52','2017-09-18 21:23:52'),('172','4NKs01dRCTTiFf3Kro214LWRSQIJq5Aq',2,'text/html','',19,'If that doesn\'t make you want to throw up, then you, my friend, have bad taste.  While I realize that a lot of this is up to the coder, the fact that CFML somewhat encourages this kind of style doesn\'t help at all.  Really, this one is more personal than should probably be mentioned here, but that has a lot to do with the proliferation of development tools.   Something about the tags.  Why brackets?','2017-09-18 21:24:03','2017-09-18 21:24:03'),('173','4NKs01dRCTTiFf3Kro214LWRSQIJq5Aq',2,'text/html','',20,'<pre>\n<html>\n<p>{{ body }}</p>\n<table>\n{{ #musty }}\n	<tr>\n		<td>musty.column1</td>\n	</tr>\n{{ /musty }}\n</table>\n</html>\n</pre>','2017-09-18 21:24:19','2017-09-18 21:24:19'),('174','4NKs01dRCTTiFf3Kro214LWRSQIJq5Aq',2,'text/html','',21,'Ah.  Like breathing without a mask.','2017-09-18 21:24:25','2017-09-18 21:24:25'),('175','4NKs01dRCTTiFf3Kro214LWRSQIJq5Aq',2,'text/html','',22,'<h3>+ Docs are everywhere</h3>','2017-09-18 21:24:30','2017-09-18 21:24:30'),('176','4NKs01dRCTTiFf3Kro214LWRSQIJq5Aq',2,'text/html','',23,'So, not only does just about everything come with Lucee, but there is pretty distinct documentation on most of the language features that ship with it.   The sites hosting CF documentation (whether it be Lucee\'s or Adobe\'s) at least succinctly explain what everything does and provide some examples on how to use it. ','2017-09-18 21:24:47','2017-09-18 21:24:47'),('177','4NKs01dRCTTiFf3Kro214LWRSQIJq5Aq',2,'text/html','',24,'One thing I always disliked about the PHP documentation was the inclusion of comments in their documentation.  You read too far and you start looking at functions that have been deprecated or far simpler ways to pull off what you were trying to pull off.  As a beginner anyway, none of that ever worked or would work in a previous version of the language ,etc.  Alwasy something.   CF seems to work fairly reliably and functions that are and are not supported by a certain version of the server are pretty clear.  It is a rare time indeed that I actually need to dig in to stackOverflow or some other site to figure something out.','2017-09-18 21:25:11','2017-09-18 21:25:11'),('178','4NKs01dRCTTiFf3Kro214LWRSQIJq5Aq',2,'text/html','',25,'<h3>- It is a bit difficult to get to the Nitty Gritty</h3>','2017-09-18 21:25:19','2017-09-18 21:25:19'),('179','4NKs01dRCTTiFf3Kro214LWRSQIJq5Aq',2,'text/html','',26,'One of PHP and Python\'s greatest strengths are in their ease of extension.  If you really need something to run fast, there is a clear documented way to do that.  Neither Lucee nor Adobe have made that process super clear.  And, of course, if it is, it\'s in Java.  ','2017-09-18 21:25:41','2017-09-18 21:25:41'),('18','eI2dETYjWLqc8ZVQNNMKYs26UQQBkaBC',2,'text/html','',0,'Try one more gain....','2017-07-03 17:26:59','2017-07-03 17:26:59'),('180','4NKs01dRCTTiFf3Kro214LWRSQIJq5Aq',2,'text/html','',27,'A notable example of this was when we considered adding SASS to our toolkit at NCCU.  The Java options were few and fiddly.  There are, however, a number of strong C and C++ libraries out there to convert these files.    Another time I\'ve wanted this capability is when adding Sqlite support to ColdMVC.  (And yes, they would probably be faster than anything I could whip out in a couple of hours on my own.)  There are apparently many ways to bind C++ code into Lucee, but this takes a fairly high level of wizardry and sifting to figure out how to do.  ','2017-09-18 21:25:45','2017-09-18 21:25:45'),('181','4NKs01dRCTTiFf3Kro214LWRSQIJq5Aq',2,'text/html','',28,'<h3>In Conclusion</h3>','2017-09-18 21:26:05','2017-09-18 21:26:05'),('182','4NKs01dRCTTiFf3Kro214LWRSQIJq5Aq',2,'text/html','',29,'So that being said, why would I advocate for the use of Lucee?   The one large integration is a big plus for me.   Even though there isn\'t a ton of ColdFusion talent still kicking about, cfscript is a pretty easy language to come to grips with.  I picked up the language and most of its idiosyncrasies within about two weeks after starting my position.  I was able to crank ColdMVC in about four hours or so, and took the rest of the week to tweak it and add more to it.  A simple framework in Node would have taken me a bit longer, forced me to force my users to download a bunch of extra stuff that they probably don\'t need, deal with dependencies not working with certain versions of a framework (cough, Rails) and of course, I would have had to write my own server and tooling to administer it.\nI long for simpler days, and I\'m one of the people who believe we can have them and still stay up to date on what\'s hot in the market.','2017-09-18 21:26:11','2017-09-18 21:26:11'),('183','Y01ojJlfoBSvAiLK8Mbq2y2jfTAEkRfD',2,'text/html','',0,'It\'s been about a year and a half since I started working at North Carolina Central University.  They are a fairly medium sized HBCU located in the middle of Durham, North Carolina and have been around since 1909.  This is my first position in higher education and a lot of things were much different than working at a regular Fortune 500 company.  One thing, I did not see coming however, is using a language for server-side development that I had not touched before.   TL;DR Lucee is not really such a bad solution for developing your web applications today, especially if you are skilled in Java or some other C-based language and do not want to deal with compilation. ','2017-09-19 15:39:37','2017-09-19 15:39:37'),('184','Y01ojJlfoBSvAiLK8Mbq2y2jfTAEkRfD',2,'text/html','',1,'At Central (short for North Carolina Central University), Lucee is the stack of choice for server-side application development.   I\'ll try to avoid any opinionated rants about the positives and negatives of that choice in this article, but instead attempt to layout an educated use case for anyone looking to deploy a website for a large organization.  To keep things fair and balanced, I\'ll lay down one negative and one positive.','2017-09-19 15:40:18','2017-09-19 15:40:18'),('185','VzXAEfNzM8I73hljC2YOLjNScxOOqWDz',2,'text/html','',0,'It\'s been about a year and a half since I started working at <a href=\"http://nccu.edu\">North Carolina Central University</a>.  They are a fairly medium sized HBCU located in the middle of Durham, North Carolina and have been around since 1909.  This is my first position in higher education and a lot of things were much different than working at a regular Fortune 500 company.  One thing, I did not see coming however, is using a language for server-side development that I had not touched before.   TL;DR Lucee is not really such a bad solution for developing your web applications today, especially if you are skilled in Java or some other C-based language and do not want to deal with compilation. ','2017-09-19 15:41:19','2017-09-19 15:41:19'),('186','VzXAEfNzM8I73hljC2YOLjNScxOOqWDz',2,'text/html','',1,'At NCCU, Lucee is the stack of choice for server-side application development.   I\'ll try to avoid any opinionated rants about the positives and negatives of that choice in this article, but instead attempt to layout an educated use case for anyone looking to deploy a website for a large organization.  To keep things fair and balanced, I\'ll lay down one negative and one positive.','2017-09-19 15:41:24','2017-09-19 15:41:24'),('187','VzXAEfNzM8I73hljC2YOLjNScxOOqWDz',2,'text/html','',2,'<h3>+ <b><i>EVERYTHING</i></b> is built-in</h3>','2017-09-19 15:41:31','2017-09-19 15:41:31'),('188','VzXAEfNzM8I73hljC2YOLjNScxOOqWDz',2,'text/html','',3,'As a web developer watching the ecosystem today, I cannot stress this point enough.  This is the single best thing about using Lucee.   I don\'t need Apache, nginx, PHP modules, junky Debian scripts, npm, babel, gradle or any of the myriad tools out there to get something running.  Working on Lucee sites has given me the advantage and freedom to just download a package, answer some questions and run the resultant script.  Here, let me show you how to get Lucee running on your system.\n','2017-09-19 15:41:36','2017-09-19 15:41:36'),('189','VzXAEfNzM8I73hljC2YOLjNScxOOqWDz',2,'text/html','',4,'<pre>\nme $ wget http://cdn.lucee.org/lucee-5.2.3.035-pl0-linux-x64-installer.run\nme $ chmod +x lucee-5.2.3.035-pl0-linux-x64-installer.run\nme $ sudo ./lucee-5.2.3.035-pl0-linux-x64-installer.run\nme $ <answer some questions>...\n</pre>','2017-09-19 15:41:41','2017-09-19 15:41:41'),('19','eI2dETYjWLqc8ZVQNNMKYs26UQQBkaBC',4,'image/jpeg','',1,'mccKZslkJnmOQvyAKaZBfLIdiWk0vZ1f.jpg','2017-07-03 17:27:02','2017-07-03 17:27:02'),('190','VzXAEfNzM8I73hljC2YOLjNScxOOqWDz',2,'text/html','',5,'Wow.  And that\'s the hard way.  You can also just use Lucee Express and hit ./startup.sh to get a server running. ','2017-09-19 15:41:47','2017-09-19 15:41:47'),('191','VzXAEfNzM8I73hljC2YOLjNScxOOqWDz',2,'text/html','',6,'So I didn\'t need to download Java, because it comes bundled with it.  The package is maybe 200 MB, which I complained about quite a bit when first starting off.  But when I think of the task that is installaing something like Laravel with probably close to half a gig of PHP packages, Javascript and Apache modules that I will probably never use again, I\'m consoled.  On a fresh system (provided that your Linux or OSX box already has everything else you need), something like the following would get Laravel running.','2017-09-19 15:41:56','2017-09-19 15:41:56'),('192','VzXAEfNzM8I73hljC2YOLjNScxOOqWDz',2,'text/html','',7,'<pre>\nme $ sudo apt-get install apache2 php composer php-{bla,bla,mcbla} # and a whole bunch of other stuff I can\'t remember right now\n# And we haven\'t even SETUP any of this yet.  It\'s just on our system...\n</pre>','2017-09-19 15:42:05','2017-09-19 15:42:05'),('193','VzXAEfNzM8I73hljC2YOLjNScxOOqWDz',2,'text/html','',8,'Most any authentication, hashing and salt methods are included in the Lucee download.  The most common database drivers ship with it (curiously enough, SQLite is missing.).   Session management ships as well and supports multiple back-ends (file, database and memory).  A mail function and an LDAP function both exist.  And, if you\'re into that sort of thing, you get a pretty well polished GUI<sup><a href=#1>1</a></sup>. ','2017-09-19 15:42:58','2017-09-19 15:42:58'),('194','VzXAEfNzM8I73hljC2YOLjNScxOOqWDz',2,'text/html','',9,'However, this brings me to my negative point.','2017-09-19 15:43:05','2017-09-19 15:43:05'),('195','VzXAEfNzM8I73hljC2YOLjNScxOOqWDz',2,'text/html','',10,'<h3>- <b><i>EVERYTHING</i></b> is included, besides a package manager...</h3>','2017-09-19 15:43:11','2017-09-19 15:43:11'),('196','VzXAEfNzM8I73hljC2YOLjNScxOOqWDz',2,'text/html','',11,'Honestly, I probably shouldn\'t have given this one a negative, but one of the reasons for the growth of communities around tools like npm and pip is because of the ubiquity of the package management aspects.   Lucee has a meager community right now (when compared to the communities using node and brethren) and as such it is a bit difficult to find modern extensions for those times you really need them.   OAuth is one big thing I can think of that there is no gold standard for.  While an OAuth implementation is not that hard to bang out (I\'ve done one in Lua before and that was with a huge shortage of libraries), it would be incredibly helpful to new users if basics like this already existed.  \n','2017-09-19 15:43:20','2017-09-19 15:43:20'),('197','VzXAEfNzM8I73hljC2YOLjNScxOOqWDz',2,'text/html','',12,'That said, there is one package manager of note rolling around. See <a href=https://www.ortussolutions.com/products/commandbox>CommandBox</a>.  Homebrew has some packages available.  I believe I was able to get it working on Cygwin.  However, I don\'t think the community is fully behind it yet and it may still be picking up speed.  There used to be <a href=\"http://www.riaforge.org\">RIAForge</a>, but that has apparently fallen out of favor.','2017-09-19 15:44:35','2017-09-19 15:44:35'),('198','VzXAEfNzM8I73hljC2YOLjNScxOOqWDz',2,'text/html','',13,'<h3>+ CFML is not the nicest language, but nothing special is needed to do some templating</h3>','2017-09-19 15:44:45','2017-09-19 15:44:45'),('199','VzXAEfNzM8I73hljC2YOLjNScxOOqWDz',2,'text/html','',14,'As web developers, it would be a bit ridiculous to say we don\'t need templating.   It would be even more ridiculous to use a framework that left templating as an afterthought.   Yes, the world has changed quite a bit since most languages came about, but pretty much all of them have kept up with this.\n','2017-09-19 15:45:06','2017-09-19 15:45:06'),('2','8T7H7D57juXfgTmtA3VmwfXJvP7v5ADS',4,'image/jpeg','',1,'fbtkCt14wVotU7coLN4OhnJe8cm0lKCQ.jpg','2017-07-03 16:43:38','2017-07-03 16:43:38'),('20','Rn0FBccMwRYgijWTc5OQAea8vAdosT1Q',2,'text/html','',0,'The first post in a very long time... Stop being jacked up','2017-07-03 17:30:10','2017-07-03 17:30:10'),('200','VzXAEfNzM8I73hljC2YOLjNScxOOqWDz',2,'text/html','',15,'I\'m not the biggest fan of the tag-based language that is CFML.  However, I do like that it facilitates writing templates without a lot of fuss. Let\'s use Mustache as an example, the logic-less wunderkind of the template universe.   It\'s one of my favorite types of templating languages because the simplicity constrains you to designing templates that avoid tons of complex logic.   Let\'s take just this example:','2017-09-19 15:45:11','2017-09-19 15:45:11'),('201','VzXAEfNzM8I73hljC2YOLjNScxOOqWDz',2,'text/html','',16,'<pre>\nI\'m your chiropractor\n{{ #condition }}\n	&lt;p&gt;It looks like you\'ve got a case of achy joints&lt;/p&gt;\n{{ /condition }}\n</pre>\n','2017-09-19 15:45:20','2017-09-19 15:45:20'),('202','VzXAEfNzM8I73hljC2YOLjNScxOOqWDz',2,'text/html','',17,'Mustache will only let you choose to display the text \'It looks like you\'ve got a case of achy joints\', depending on the <i>boolean</i> value of \'condition\'.  However, what if I were looping through a database query and \'condition\' was a number or, even better yet, a string defining a particular health condition?  To solve that in CF would be pretty trivial( if a little verbose ). ','2017-09-19 15:45:48','2017-09-19 15:45:48'),('203','VzXAEfNzM8I73hljC2YOLjNScxOOqWDz',2,'text/html','',18,'<pre>\n&lt;cfif condition eq 1&gt;\n	&lt;p&gt;It looks like you\'ve got a case of achy joints&lt;/p&gt;\n&lt;cfelseif condition eq 2&gt;\n	&lt;p&gt;Oh no!  It looks like you\'ve got a case of bronchitis&lt;/p&gt;\n&lt;cfelseif condition eq 3&gt;\n	&lt;p&gt;It looks like you\'ve got a case of a broken heart&lt;/p&gt;\n&lt;cfelse&gt;\n	&lt;p&gt;Hey!  Get out of here!  There\'s nothing wrong with you&lt;/p&gt;\n&lt;/cfif&gt;\n</pre>','2017-09-19 15:45:54','2017-09-19 15:45:54'),('204','VzXAEfNzM8I73hljC2YOLjNScxOOqWDz',2,'text/html','',19,'Now of course, this can get out of hand really fast and it takes a fair bit of discipline on the developer\'s part to keep the businesss logic and views seperate.  Rails, Laravel and other modern frameworks excel at this.  Lucee ships with no capabilities to make this possible, but it is forgivable because <i>I don\'t need any other libraries to make it happen.</i>.  But this brings me to my negative point...\n','2017-09-19 15:46:39','2017-09-19 15:46:39'),('205','VzXAEfNzM8I73hljC2YOLjNScxOOqWDz',2,'text/html','',20,'<h3>- CFML is not the nicest language.  Period.</h3>','2017-09-19 15:46:47','2017-09-19 15:46:47'),('206','VzXAEfNzM8I73hljC2YOLjNScxOOqWDz',2,'text/html','',21,'<pre>\n&lt;cfquery name=\"etc\" datasource=\"yourmom\"&gt;\nSELECT * FROM no_fs_given \nWHERE user = \'superman\' AND status = 12\n&lt;/cfquery&gt;\n&lt;cfsavecontent variable=\"GreetingText\"&gt;\nHello, and welcome to this spiffy webpage.\nIt\'s purty, ain\'t it?\n&lt;/cfsavecontent&gt;\n&lt;cfset bla=0&gt;\n\n&lt;html&gt;\n&lt;body&gt;\n	&lt;p&gt;\n	&lt;cfoutput&gt;#GreetingText#&lt;cfoutput&gt;\n	&lt;/p&gt;\n	&lt;table&gt;\n	&lt;cfloop query=\"etc\"&gt;\n		&lt;tr&gt;\n		&lt;cfif bla gt 3&gt;\n			&lt;td&gt;#column1#&lt;/td&gt;\n		&lt;cfelse&gt;\n			&lt;td&gt;Nothing at all&lt;/td&gt;\n		&lt;/cfif&gt;\n			&lt;td&gt;#column2#&lt;/td&gt;\n			&lt;td&gt;#column3#&lt;/td&gt;\n		&lt;/tr&gt;\n		&lt;cfset bla=bla+1&gt;\n	&lt;/cfloop&gt;\n	&lt;/table&gt;\n&lt;/body&gt;\n&lt;/html&gt;\n</pre>','2017-09-19 15:46:56','2017-09-19 15:46:56'),('207','VzXAEfNzM8I73hljC2YOLjNScxOOqWDz',2,'text/html','',22,'If that doesn\'t make you want to throw up, then you, my friend, have bad taste.  As stated earlier, a lot of this is up to the developer.  And yes, this example is badly written to prove a point.  But the fact that CFML somewhat encourages this kind of style doesn\'t help at all.  Now let\'s take a look at some fairly clean Mustache.','2017-09-19 15:47:33','2017-09-19 15:47:33'),('208','VzXAEfNzM8I73hljC2YOLjNScxOOqWDz',2,'text/html','',23,'<pre>\n&lt;html&gt;\n&lt;body&gt;\n&lt;p&gt;{{ GreetingText }}&lt;/p&gt;\n&lt;table&gt;\n{{ #etc }}\n	&lt;tr&gt;\n		&lt;td&gt;{{ column1 }}&lt;/td&gt;\n		&lt;td&gt;{{ column2 }}&lt;/td&gt;\n		&lt;td&gt;{{ column3 }}&lt;/td&gt;\n	&lt;/tr&gt;\n{{ /etc }}\n&lt;/table&gt;\n&lt;/body&gt;\n&lt;/html&gt;\n</pre>','2017-09-19 15:47:39','2017-09-19 15:47:39'),('209','VzXAEfNzM8I73hljC2YOLjNScxOOqWDz',2,'text/html','',24,'Ah.  Like breathing without a mask.','2017-09-19 15:47:46','2017-09-19 15:47:46'),('21','Rn0FBccMwRYgijWTc5OQAea8vAdosT1Q',4,'image/jpeg','',1,'oJLMrRtdk1Dt8XGqiAvGWFflw74GfttX.jpg','2017-07-03 17:30:13','2017-07-03 17:30:13'),('210','VzXAEfNzM8I73hljC2YOLjNScxOOqWDz',2,'text/html','',25,'In fairness, my aversion to the the tag based language is more a matter of personal taste than anything else.\nIt looks a bit too much like HTML and is not always supported by popular code editors.\nOne of the interns in our department loves Sublime Text and, surprisingly, an easy to install plugin could not be found for the language.\nAdditionally, it\'s not consistent.  Certain tags close, others don\'t.   Named parameters are not always easy to guess at and roll with, so this kind of hurts productivity.    \nQueries are referenced using strings and not using hashes (e.g. \'myQuery\' vs \'#myQuery#\' ), but lists are the opposite.\nAgain, minor niggles, but you can get an idea as to why some of these things are not useful when looking for a language that will last for a while.  ','2017-09-19 15:49:49','2017-09-19 15:49:49'),('211','VzXAEfNzM8I73hljC2YOLjNScxOOqWDz',2,'text/html','',26,'<h3>+ Docs are everywhere</h3>','2017-09-19 15:50:08','2017-09-19 15:50:08'),('212','VzXAEfNzM8I73hljC2YOLjNScxOOqWDz',2,'text/html','',27,'So, not only does just about everything come with Lucee, but there is pretty distinct documentation on most of the language features that ship with it.   The sites hosting CF documentation (whether it be <a href=\"http://docs.lucee.org/reference/functions.html\">Lucee\'s</a> or <a href=\"https://helpx.adobe.com/coldfusion/cfml-reference/topics.html\">Adobe\'s</a> or <a href=\"https://cfdocs.org/\">this one</a>) at least succinctly explain what everything does and provide some examples on how to use it.   ','2017-09-19 15:54:40','2017-09-19 15:54:40'),('213','VzXAEfNzM8I73hljC2YOLjNScxOOqWDz',2,'text/html','',28,'One thing I always disliked about the PHP documentation was the inclusion of comments in their documentation.  You read too far and you start looking at functions that have been deprecated or far simpler ways to pull off what you were trying to pull off.  As a beginner anyway, none of that ever worked or would work in a previous version of the language, etc.  I felt like there always something extra I needed to think about.  CFML seems to work fairly reliably across its many available versions and functions that are and are not supported by a certain version of the server are pretty clear.  It is a rare time indeed that I actually need to visit StackOverflow or some other site to figure something out.','2017-09-19 15:56:36','2017-09-19 15:56:36'),('214','VzXAEfNzM8I73hljC2YOLjNScxOOqWDz',2,'text/html','',29,'<h3>- It is a bit difficult to get to the Nitty Gritty</h3>','2017-09-19 15:56:41','2017-09-19 15:56:41'),('215','VzXAEfNzM8I73hljC2YOLjNScxOOqWDz',2,'text/html','',30,'One of PHP and Python\'s greatest strengths are in their ease of extension.  If you really need something to run fast or are looking to integrate the hottest new message queue library into your application, there is a clear documented way to do that.  Neither Lucee nor Adobe have made that process super clear.  And, of course, Java is going to be your preferred option.  ','2017-09-19 15:58:55','2017-09-19 15:58:55'),('216','VzXAEfNzM8I73hljC2YOLjNScxOOqWDz',2,'text/html','',31,'A notable example of this was when we considered adding SASS to our toolkit at Central.  The Java options were few and fiddly.  There are, however, a number of strong C and C++ libraries out there to convert these files.    Another time I\'ve wanted this capability is when adding SQLite support to ColdMVC.  There are apparently some ways to bind C++ code into Lucee, but this takes a fairly high level of wizardry and sifting to figure out how to do.  ','2017-09-19 16:00:53','2017-09-19 16:00:53'),('217','VzXAEfNzM8I73hljC2YOLjNScxOOqWDz',2,'text/html','',32,'<h3>+ Ease of Use</h3>','2017-09-19 16:01:00','2017-09-19 16:01:00'),('218','VzXAEfNzM8I73hljC2YOLjNScxOOqWDz',2,'text/html','',33,'Lucee is pretty darn simple to get running.  It\'s also easy to be productive.  When starting my position, I was productive with cfscript after about a month being at Central. (The first two weeks were spent peeking around the mostly CFML codebase and trying to figure out what I\'m dealing with).  I\'m fairly strong in programming and know about 5 other languages well.   But even if you\'re a greenhorn, you\'ll be able to figure out how to get rolling.  We are not dealing with Haskell here, with its monads and other mythical species <sup><a href=#2>2</a></sup>.  Also, for the Java/C#/Go heads, no compilation is needed.  I don\'t have a problem with compilation, but dynamic websites driven mostly by text really don\'t have a need for those sorts of things.','2017-09-19 16:01:05','2017-09-19 16:01:05'),('219','VzXAEfNzM8I73hljC2YOLjNScxOOqWDz',2,'text/html','',34,'<h3>- Talent May be a Bit Short</h3>','2017-09-19 16:01:11','2017-09-19 16:01:11'),('22','NdVl16dRAzYnmMKdvDgo3r7lNFHUUvYz',4,'image/jpeg','',0,'R4KkNl2ZORDL0NMy8jaNmvBmihqyLeJb.jpg','2017-07-03 17:33:41','2017-07-03 17:33:41'),('220','VzXAEfNzM8I73hljC2YOLjNScxOOqWDz',2,'text/html','',35,'CF is old.  Like \"Dave Mustaine, Gene Simmons and Public Enemy Do America Tour\" old.   Lucee is not the first attempt at open-sourcing the CFML engine.   (It is arguably one of the best though, and the most well supported currently.)  Because of the language\'s age, CF talent may be running few and far between.   ColdFusion talent is up there with COBOL talent as far as the animals in the ecosystem.   Just something to be aware of.','2017-09-19 16:01:15','2017-09-19 16:01:15'),('221','VzXAEfNzM8I73hljC2YOLjNScxOOqWDz',2,'text/html','',36,'<h3>In Conclusion</h3>','2017-09-19 16:01:20','2017-09-19 16:01:20'),('222','VzXAEfNzM8I73hljC2YOLjNScxOOqWDz',2,'text/html','',37,'After all of this, why would I advocate for the use of Lucee?   The one large integration is a big plus for me.   Even though there isn\'t a ton of ColdFusion talent still kicking about, cfscript is a pretty easy language to come to grips with.  I picked up the language in about two weeks, most of CF\'s quirks within about two months and banged out a simple framework in about four hours within three months after starting my position.  I didn\'t even mention all of the other really super well written frameworks that are already out there.  <a href=\"http://framework-one.github.io/\">Framework One</a> by Sean Corfield is a popular solution and pretty lightweight and easy to get around for a seasoned Java dev.   <a href=\"https://www.ortussolutions.com/products/coldbox\">ColdBox</a> is the product of Ortus Solutions, and comes with a bunch of tooling in the form of CommandBox.   It makes your ColdFusion sites act like node sites.   A simple framework in Node would have taken me a bit longer, forced me to force my users to download a bunch of extra stuff that they probably don\'t need, deal with dependencies not working with certain versions of a framework (*cough* Rails) and of course, I would have had to write my own server and tooling to administer it. Express is a situation where this is done well, but its still a lot to just get a website on the screen.   I long for simpler days, and I\'m one of the people who believe we can have them and still stay up to date on what\'s hot in the market.','2017-09-19 16:03:50','2017-09-19 16:03:50'),('223','VzXAEfNzM8I73hljC2YOLjNScxOOqWDz',2,'text/html','',38,'<h3>Footnotes</h3>\n<ol>\n<li>\n<a id=1>The Lucee devs clearly spend a great deal of time tuning their server\'s GUI.  It is a quality tool, but I do try to avoid it because I really dig command line tooling.</a>\n</li>\n<li>\n<a id=2>I don\'t have any problems with Haskell.  Hopefully the humor is coming across here...</a>\n</li>\n</ol>\n','2017-09-19 16:04:03','2017-09-19 16:04:03'),('224','sVfalFnz3jM1rUZ28mmYWgDesBzvhjTv',2,'text/html','',0,'Do you ever need to extract strange packages to your Linux system?   Occasionally, vendors will package scripts or binaries as a tarball and kindly omit a Makefile or other scripts to handle installation.  While running an experiment with OSS a few months ago, I saw myself trying to figure out how this worked.  So the next time you run into a binary package that is distributed this way, try this to make short work of it:\n\n<pre>\ntar xzf file.tar.gz -C /target/dir --strip-components=1\n</pre>\n\n<p>\n\n</p>','2017-09-19 18:03:11','2017-09-19 18:03:11'),('225','xoO3ZzvsQtoJ3bihcGf8oGGeGt0WfSTG',2,'text/html','',0,'Today is a new day.','2017-09-22 17:24:16','2017-09-22 17:24:16'),('226','xoO3ZzvsQtoJ3bihcGf8oGGeGt0WfSTG',4,'image/jpeg','',1,'K3OsOm3nMrw6dNECFDBABwTygU7ZlZW0.jpg','2017-09-22 17:25:26','2017-09-22 17:25:26'),('227','xoO3ZzvsQtoJ3bihcGf8oGGeGt0WfSTG',4,'image/jpeg','',2,'uFZsfRyftzC0gNWGnM4wqUaxitH2CmvT.jpg','2017-09-22 17:28:27','2017-09-22 17:28:27'),('228','xoO3ZzvsQtoJ3bihcGf8oGGeGt0WfSTG',2,'text/html','',3,'If only you could be here with me.','2017-09-22 17:28:37','2017-09-22 17:28:37'),('229','y8g4K6uCzbVk4tudFXD00lYfOSG3IVio',2,'text/html','',0,'Using find on Linux can be extremely helpful.  Using xargs is the way to make it happen.  If you ever need to find a directory full of files with a specific criteria and just copy the matches, this combination makes that possible.  The following would copy all *.c files to the fold/ directory.\n\n<pre>\n$ find -type f -name \"*.c\" | xargs -ISRC cp SRC fold/\n</pre>\n  \nSupposing you\'re in the real world, where file names often have spaces in them, adding the -print0 and -0 flags to find and xargs respectively, will make that command line work pretty much anywhere.\n','2017-09-29 00:02:30','2017-09-29 00:02:30'),('23','NdVl16dRAzYnmMKdvDgo3r7lNFHUUvYz',2,'text/html','',1,'wow, what a shiba','2017-07-03 17:33:45','2017-07-03 17:33:45'),('230','5VCm2yYWa7HeKtchqYwubK3UoOC3FbBK',2,'text/html','',0,'It\'s been about 2 weeks since I returned from San Franscisco, CA.  I had an interesting time there and saw most of the things people blog about.','2017-10-02 15:53:51','2017-10-02 15:53:51'),('231','yWbXmdC2sG0Ivh6TeCxaLYsqRWwHRIMY',2,'text/html','',0,'It\'s been about two weeks since I returned from San Francisco.   I knew no one, but was able to meet a few people in my hostel as well as around town at coffee shops and whatnot.  I even met a goodly fellow in the terminal on the plane ride home.   Unfortunately, I didn\'t spend nearly enough time there.  How foolish to think I would be able to see the entire city in just four days.   It wasn\'t all for naught though.  I was able to get some great pics and see a side of the U.S. I have not seen before.','2017-10-02 16:07:50','2017-10-02 16:07:50'),('232','yWbXmdC2sG0Ivh6TeCxaLYsqRWwHRIMY',4,'image/jpeg','',1,'4BvD7rESCExlNQXKWIuWsvDeg2Rat1eH.jpg','2017-10-02 16:09:24','2017-10-02 16:09:24'),('233','yWbXmdC2sG0Ivh6TeCxaLYsqRWwHRIMY',2,'text/html','',2,'<small><i>Some block in SOMA.</i></small>','2017-10-02 16:09:39','2017-10-02 16:09:39'),('234','yWbXmdC2sG0Ivh6TeCxaLYsqRWwHRIMY',4,'image/jpeg','',3,'35hqIDgt0JRdQnckfIQsGtbviFOhVqgv.jpg','2017-10-02 16:12:13','2017-10-02 16:12:13'),('235','yWbXmdC2sG0Ivh6TeCxaLYsqRWwHRIMY',2,'text/html','',4,'<small><i>A payphone? In San Fran?</i></small>','2017-10-02 16:13:12','2017-10-02 16:13:12'),('236','yWbXmdC2sG0Ivh6TeCxaLYsqRWwHRIMY',4,'image/jpeg','',5,'YW5CIqi8rbHfdF73EdMmXMqnBHUZFqvb.jpg','2017-10-02 16:14:52','2017-10-02 16:14:52'),('237','yWbXmdC2sG0Ivh6TeCxaLYsqRWwHRIMY',2,'text/html','',6,'<small><i>Clearly should have invested in a better phone for this.  Oh yeah, this is the Orpheum: a pretty popular theater near SOMA</i></small>','2017-10-02 16:15:28','2017-10-02 16:15:28'),('238','yWbXmdC2sG0Ivh6TeCxaLYsqRWwHRIMY',4,'image/jpeg','',7,'vOvrbT42UAJJNln2NWqZfEtFKwFSldwt.jpg','2017-10-02 16:17:05','2017-10-02 16:17:05'),('239','yWbXmdC2sG0Ivh6TeCxaLYsqRWwHRIMY',2,'text/html','',8,'<small><i><b>NOT</b> Golden Gate.  I was too lazy to get out there, but instead spent lots of time in the southern portions of the city.</i></small>','2017-10-02 16:17:48','2017-10-02 16:17:48'),('24','5L14g3XGVa4h7qUvAaiErgZoUvEeUll4',2,'text/html','',0,'Oh my Days. I\'ve jump-started my blog and jump started my life to more accurately reflect what I do. I\'ve had lots of time to think and brood over my path. I really enjoy what I do and want to start telling the world about it.','2017-07-04 15:53:36','2017-07-04 15:53:36'),('240','yWbXmdC2sG0Ivh6TeCxaLYsqRWwHRIMY',4,'image/jpeg','',9,'MCtwdhyNt6q30ABFL1c7QhqA66J3VswZ.jpg','2017-10-02 16:18:09','2017-10-02 16:18:09'),('241','yWbXmdC2sG0Ivh6TeCxaLYsqRWwHRIMY',2,'text/html','',10,'<small><i>So, this isn\'t even San Francisco... but I thought it was worth putting up.  This is the Denver Airport.  Do not plan anything if you come here.  You are too far away from the city and it is prohibitively expense to get there via Uber.</i></small>','2017-10-02 16:19:30','2017-10-02 16:19:30'),('242','yWbXmdC2sG0Ivh6TeCxaLYsqRWwHRIMY',4,'image/jpeg','',11,'1JUYWJFzoK6F40mMRhE0cOYZ8E7rnguk.jpg','2017-10-02 16:19:47','2017-10-02 16:19:47'),('243','yWbXmdC2sG0Ivh6TeCxaLYsqRWwHRIMY',2,'text/html','',12,'<small><i>Dark block in the Financial District</i></small>','2017-10-02 16:20:00','2017-10-02 16:20:00'),('244','yWbXmdC2sG0Ivh6TeCxaLYsqRWwHRIMY',4,'image/jpeg','',13,'mDuByuYdw0CrRQmSx0qMhA3DXcKUrxtz.jpg','2017-10-02 16:20:13','2017-10-02 16:20:13'),('245','yWbXmdC2sG0Ivh6TeCxaLYsqRWwHRIMY',2,'text/html','',14,'<small><i>San Jose.  meh.</i></small>','2017-10-02 16:20:28','2017-10-02 16:20:28'),('246','yWbXmdC2sG0Ivh6TeCxaLYsqRWwHRIMY',2,'text/html','',15,'If you made it here, you have just seen a stream of consciousness.   I\'ll have more pictures later on.','2017-10-02 16:20:54','2017-10-02 16:20:54'),('247','VENfE3yLUJH0JgTHESnX1wSO4GeaCt7O',2,'text/html','',0,'The intro text of this particular blog would look something like.','2017-10-02 18:44:43','2017-10-02 18:44:43'),('248','VENfE3yLUJH0JgTHESnX1wSO4GeaCt7O',4,'image/jpeg','',1,'63GzSY4gJi2KH7t1R2bk1VcdoeSsyfBg.jpg','2017-10-02 18:44:51','2017-10-02 18:44:51'),('249','VENfE3yLUJH0JgTHESnX1wSO4GeaCt7O',2,'text/html','',2,'Let\'s put in some outro text as well.','2017-10-02 18:45:06','2017-10-02 18:45:06'),('25','5L14g3XGVa4h7qUvAaiErgZoUvEeUll4',2,'text/html','',1,'As of today March 20th, 2017, I will have two more weeks as an Analyst at North Carolina Central University. I have learned a new language here, tested my Javascript skills and learned to work with a team. I\'ve also gotten a glimpse into how colleges work and what kinds of issues they deal with.','2017-07-04 15:53:45','2017-07-04 15:53:45'),('250','fkLXNxezvTqETNOHjHWVzmNYxw1Lwewd',2,'text/html','',0,'It\'s October 8th, 2017.  I just saw Blade Runner with some friends (well, really one friend) that I haven\'t seen in a while, and a whole lot of people I\'ve never met.    Its nice to be around folks who can enjoy a good movie.  But enough of that....  The new Blade Runner is a hell of a flick.   It is a bit simpler (if not longer) than its predecessor.   It seems as if Ridley Scott is intentionally being less obtuse than the first film.','2017-10-08 21:44:59','2017-10-08 21:44:59'),('251','lLnIZVlHgb6zbm5TGJduQWf7fCxfe2jB',2,'text/html','',0,'Hello, world.','2017-10-10 16:46:39','2017-10-10 16:46:39'),('252','lLnIZVlHgb6zbm5TGJduQWf7fCxfe2jB',4,'image/jpeg','',1,'hgDBowejr8wL8XbGlxeSrKS7h0AKUgSC.jpg','2017-10-10 16:47:01','2017-10-10 16:47:01'),('253','lLnIZVlHgb6zbm5TGJduQWf7fCxfe2jB',2,'text/html','',2,'End of post.','2017-10-10 16:47:05','2017-10-10 16:47:05'),('254','tuSmmOtGqKfsGg1HyaBsdjtkuoBOlfvm',4,'image/jpeg','',0,'Dj5hMoxvvLkIolU1WBDE4JbY8NaagsID.jpg','2017-10-17 15:17:29','2017-10-17 15:17:29'),('255','tuSmmOtGqKfsGg1HyaBsdjtkuoBOlfvm',2,'text/html','',1,'Bla...','2017-10-17 15:17:32','2017-10-17 15:17:32'),('256','2RgL1JvBfz72QdShJZkxGVQCXqWxL10W',2,'text/html','',0,'Clowns.  So scary...   I don\'t think I\'ll be seeing it this weekend.  Follow the jump for the scariest thing you\'ve ever seen.','2017-10-17 15:20:07','2017-10-17 15:20:07'),('257','2RgL1JvBfz72QdShJZkxGVQCXqWxL10W',2,'text/html','',0,'It, might just be the movie for me.  I\'ve never been scared of clowns.   It\'s just a creepy man in makeup after all.','2017-10-17 15:21:06','2017-10-17 15:21:06'),('258','2RgL1JvBfz72QdShJZkxGVQCXqWxL10W',4,'image/jpeg','',1,'15vLjOku8DeOSM7iD5K5AldXNWTxUh1B.jpg','2017-10-17 15:21:08','2017-10-17 15:21:08'),('259','2RgL1JvBfz72QdShJZkxGVQCXqWxL10W',2,'text/html','',2,'Awww, look at that face.  He\'s like a little murderous chipmunk.','2017-10-17 15:21:23','2017-10-17 15:21:23'),('26','UxxUDWOHw2QUfUrWuixIU1v5hcRZKils',2,'text/html','',0,'Oh my Days. I\'ve jump-started my blog and jump started my life to more accurately reflect what I do. I\'ve had lots of time to think and brood over my path. I really enjoy what I do and want to start telling the world about it.','2017-07-04 15:53:55','2017-07-04 15:53:55'),('260','TNJxKT4HNsdsxF4A4saVUJI8Ax7TFvON',2,'text/html','',0,'draft mode','2017-10-17 15:30:02','2017-10-17 15:30:02'),('261','TNJxKT4HNsdsxF4A4saVUJI8Ax7TFvON',4,'image/jpeg','',1,'VuHX2gdEbadoXIVET1J3yuibd7X6FiYR.jpg','2017-10-17 15:30:09','2017-10-17 15:30:09'),('262','TNJxKT4HNsdsxF4A4saVUJI8Ax7TFvON',2,'text/html','',2,'yeah','2017-10-17 15:30:30','2017-10-17 15:30:30'),('263','JjndKgxq81zn6hk6TTtOHKkCojYAJyxN',2,'text/html','',0,'There is some work going on here.','2017-10-24 13:42:45','2017-10-24 13:42:45'),('264','JjndKgxq81zn6hk6TTtOHKkCojYAJyxN',4,'image/jpeg','',1,'2oWs6cJHOcsYJ3sNoxJkxI2bBZhD3Vvd.jpg','2017-10-24 13:45:54','2017-10-24 13:45:54'),('265','JjndKgxq81zn6hk6TTtOHKkCojYAJyxN',2,'text/html','',2,'Ooh, look at that Mercedes.','2017-10-24 13:46:02','2017-10-24 13:46:02'),('266','hDtBOhyQ5Lbt7nlAtHWCMvSG06ytWnw2',2,'text/html','',0,'I have lots of things I\'d like to say.','2017-10-24 13:53:51','2017-10-24 13:53:51'),('267','hDtBOhyQ5Lbt7nlAtHWCMvSG06ytWnw2',2,'text/html','',1,'<pre>\nint main (int argc, char *argv)\n{\n\n}','2017-10-24 13:54:05','2017-10-24 13:54:05'),('268','hDtBOhyQ5Lbt7nlAtHWCMvSG06ytWnw2',2,'text/html','',3,'Ooh, look!  It\'s a fancy car...','2017-10-24 13:54:22','2017-10-24 13:54:22'),('269','6XmhVfY5hxGf71WzLoIRX6vGhemlssav',2,'text/html','',0,'Bla bla bla','2017-10-24 14:06:58','2017-10-24 14:06:58'),('27','UxxUDWOHw2QUfUrWuixIU1v5hcRZKils',2,'text/html','',1,'It\'s , I will have two more weeks as an Analyst at North Carolina Central University. I have learned a new language here, tested my Javascript skills and learned to work with a team. I\'ve also gotten a glimpse into how colleges work and what kinds of issues they deal with.','2017-07-04 15:54:35','2017-07-04 15:54:35'),('270','jn8KNbiCerGiFMcGKWFdLoVrcq2sGAQ3',2,'text/html','',0,'So this is kind of an admission.  I never really understood C++.   I\'ve always wondered why people use it.   Until I read what Stroustroup actually thought about it.  For some reason, everything got EXTREMELY clear.','2017-11-06 16:44:21','2017-11-06 16:44:21'),('271','jn8KNbiCerGiFMcGKWFdLoVrcq2sGAQ3',2,'text/html','',1,'<pre>\n// Quick guide to classes\n\n\ninvariants.. the common elements between all objects of a a class\n\n// constructors:\n	<name of funct>( .. ) { ... }\n	\n// destructors:\n	~<name of funct> ( ... ) { ... }\n	\n	\n// classes can be interfaces...?\nclass Driver {\npublic:\n	virtual int read( char *p, int n ) = 0;\n	virtual bool reset() = 0;\n	virtual Status check() = 0;\n};\n\nclass Driver1 : public Driver { // a driver\n	public:\n		Driver1(Register);	// constructor\n		int read(char*, int n);	\n		bool reset();\n		Status check();\n	private:\n		// implementation details, incl. representation\n	};\n\nclass Driver2 : public Driver { // another driver\n	public:\n		Driver2(Register);\n		int read(char*, int n);	\n		bool reset();\n		Status check();\n	private:\n		// implementation details, incl., representation\n	};\n</pre>','2017-11-06 16:44:50','2017-11-06 16:44:50'),('272','jn8KNbiCerGiFMcGKWFdLoVrcq2sGAQ3',2,'text/html','',2,'I wrote a little write up on it.  And will share it with the world.  Just cause...  \n','2017-11-06 16:45:31','2017-11-06 16:45:31'),('273','GF8YnjgTDgq05Yf8ocA4Of6hKzwHiWdL',2,'text/html','',0,'aaa','2017-11-21 18:37:29','2017-11-21 18:37:29'),('274','GF8YnjgTDgq05Yf8ocA4Of6hKzwHiWdL',4,'image/jpeg','',1,'CkQFZEc0XuzggWZrXIkuUBjnANZVWAez.jpg','2017-11-21 18:37:33','2017-11-21 18:37:33'),('275','GF8YnjgTDgq05Yf8ocA4Of6hKzwHiWdL',4,'image/jpeg','',2,'EIe7nHH0YE3Jarj8bhQOi8C6dN72tECK.jpg','2017-11-21 18:37:36','2017-11-21 18:37:36'),('276','GF8YnjgTDgq05Yf8ocA4Of6hKzwHiWdL',2,'text/html','',3,'done\n','2017-11-21 18:37:44','2017-11-21 18:37:44'),('277','reRkEFMXo5GbdyI0HtA2YagXIVbJVvJe',2,'text/html','',0,'About a month and a half ago, my new Macbook Pro was made off with.  Pissed me off for a while, then I just stopped caring.  Either way, I\'ve got to find a new laptop, but I\'m really thinking about my purchase before I go ahead and do it.  There are a lot of factors present that I hadn\'t thought about much at all.','2017-12-21 20:24:27','2017-12-21 20:24:27'),('278','reRkEFMXo5GbdyI0HtA2YagXIVbJVvJe',2,'text/html','',1,'For instance, I didn\'t know that the Retina supported such a high resolution (5100 x 2200 or something ridiculous like that).  From a pure design perspective I want this just to see what potential designs will look like.  ','2017-12-21 20:25:52','2017-12-21 20:25:52'),('279','18k1vyjRtSkkY0y8mo0CCkQj8YmKL0Wm',2,'text/html','',0,'<p>\nVMs suck.  They\'re kind of a necessary element for the tools we\'re using, but let\'s be real.  They suck.  There are always lots of things to configure and lots of extra to do.   Seeing as though I always have to do this, here\'s a quick guide to getting Debian set up on a new system.  We\'re going to use VirtualBox as a hypervisor.  Your host operating system doesn\'t matter.   If you haven\'t already installed it, get VirtualBox and install it.\n</p>\n\n\n<p>\n<ol>\n<li>\nCreate a disk (or two) depending on needs.  Also make sure that two ethernet interfaces are plugged in.\nThe other must be hostonly, so that I can log in from my current box.\n</li>\n<li>\nInstall Debian\n</li>\n<li>\nReboot, login as root.\n</li>\n<li>\nInstall your favorite editor and sudo\n<pre>\n$ apt-get install sudo vim\n</pre>\n</li>\n<li>\nEdit the /etc/network/interfaces file to listen to two fake ethernet interfaces.\n<pre>\n# check the ip addresses and find the one that is NOT bound to an  IP address\n$ ip addr\n...\n</pre>\n<pre>\nallow-hotplug enp0s8\niface enp0s8 inet static\naddress 192.168.56.101\nbroadcast 255.255.255.0\n</pre>\n</li>\n<li>\nHarden up SSH just slightly\n<pre>\n$ vim /etc/ssh/sshd_config\n\n# Add AllowUsers, Disable passwords for SSH auth and force key file authentication\nAllowUsers $USER\n</pre>\n</li>\n<li>\nGenerate a private key from your other box\n<pre>\n$ ssh-keygen yourKey\n</pre>\n</li>\n<li>\nCopy it to the new box (more than likely at 192.168.56.101)\n<pre>\nssh root@192.168.56.101 \"test -d /home/$USER/.ssh || mkdir /home/$USER/.ssh\"\nscp yourKey.pub 192.168.56.101:/home/$USER/.ssh/\nssh root@192.168.56.101 \"cat /home/$USER/.ssh/yourKey.pub >> /home/$USER/.ssh/authorized_keys && rm /home/$USER/.ssh/yourKey.pub\"\n</pre>\n</li>\n<li>\nRestart the ssh daemon and networking modules\n<pre>\nssh root@192.168.56.101\nservice network restart \nservice sshd restart \n</pre>\n</li>\n<li>\nCheck that the key works\n<pre>\nssh $USER@192.168.56.101\n</pre>\n</li>\n</ol>\n</p>','2018-01-30 21:01:51','2018-01-30 21:01:51'),('28','M5MZE6UVLCXEySFGtLEi0XVB22Uthw5s',2,'text/html','',0,'Learning Vim was a somewhat daunting process for me.  I trudged through some documentation and a ton of forums to learn how to use it.  The most effective way for me to learn it, though, was to just <i>stick</i> with it.  It took about a year before I finally mastered it.  So, if you\'re new to Vim, check this post and see if you find anything useful to make your learning process move a bit more smoothly.','2017-07-04 15:56:48','2017-07-04 15:56:48'),('280','y0DymGrWuegMYoMG53WFIOBhABVO2XtJ',2,'text/html','',0,'<p>\nVMs suck.  They\'re kind of a necessary element for the tools we\'re using, but let\'s be real.  They suck.  There are always lots of things to configure and lots of extra to do.   Seeing as though I always have to do this, here\'s a quick guide to getting Debian set up on a system.   We\'re going to use VirtualBox as a hypervisor.  Your host operating system doesn\'t matter.\n</p>','2018-01-30 21:06:04','2018-01-30 21:06:04'),('281','y0DymGrWuegMYoMG53WFIOBhABVO2XtJ',2,'text/html','',1,'<p>\nIf you don\'t already have <a href=\"https://www.virtualbox.org/wiki/Downloads\">VirtualBox</a>, download it and install it.   You\'ll also need a Debian disk.  <a href=\"https://www.debian.org/CD/netinst/\">This page</a> will get you a copy.\n</p>','2018-01-30 21:06:08','2018-01-30 21:06:08'),('282','y0DymGrWuegMYoMG53WFIOBhABVO2XtJ',2,'text/html','',2,'<p>\n<ol>\n<li>\nCreate a disk (or two) depending on needs.  Also make sure that two ethernet interfaces are plugged in.\nThe other must be hostonly, so that I can log in from my current box.\n</li>\n<li>\nInstall Debian\n</li>\n<li>\nReboot, login as root.\n</li>\n<li>\nInstall your favorite editor and sudo\n<pre>\n$ apt-get install sudo vim\n</pre>\n</li>\n<li>\nEdit the /etc/network/interfaces file to listen to two fake ethernet interfaces.\n<pre>\n# check the ip addresses and find the one that is NOT bound to an  IP address\n$ ip addr\n...\n</pre>\n<pre>\nallow-hotplug enp0s8\niface enp0s8 inet static\naddress 192.168.56.101\nbroadcast 255.255.255.0\n</pre>\n</li>\n<li>\nHarden up SSH just slightly\n<pre>\n$ vim /etc/ssh/sshd_config\n\n# Add AllowUsers, Disable passwords for SSH auth and force key file authentication\nAllowUsers $USER\n</pre>\n</li>\n<li>\nGenerate a private key from your other box\n<pre>\n$ ssh-keygen yourKey\n</pre>\n</li>\n<li>\nCopy it to the new box (more than likely at 192.168.56.101)\n<pre>\nssh root@192.168.56.101 \"test -d /home/$USER/.ssh || mkdir /home/$USER/.ssh\"\nscp yourKey.pub 192.168.56.101:/home/$USER/.ssh/\nssh root@192.168.56.101 \"cat /home/$USER/.ssh/yourKey.pub >> /home/$USER/.ssh/authorized_keys && rm /home/$USER/.ssh/yourKey.pub\"\n</pre>\n</li>\n<li>\nRestart the ssh daemon and networking modules\n<pre>\nssh root@192.168.56.101\nservice network restart \nservice sshd restart \n</pre>\n</li>\n<li>\nCheck that the key works\n<pre>\nssh $USER@192.168.56.101\n</pre>\n</li>\n</ol>\n</p>','2018-01-30 21:06:14','2018-01-30 21:06:14'),('283','GTDMYKeEGLMVreX6C0Kzsk25UVqCAQJm',2,'text/html','',0,'Have you ever been in a place so long that you start forgetting simple things?  It\'s reaching that time after about 2 and a half years of being back in North Carolina.  It\'s time to leave.   ','2018-06-16 19:25:05','2018-06-16 19:25:05'),('284','Ijcy7FBrMnH5CEFFMbNwFKmf5xYeXKyJ',2,'text/html','',0,'I recently moved to Winston-Salem to continue work on a contract I was awarded.  I am six months in on the project now and still plugging away.   I\'ve needed an actual break from it for a while, but have not gotten the chance.   So I decided to force one and visit the Northeast again.\n','2018-07-30 11:54:55','2018-07-30 11:54:55'),('285','Ijcy7FBrMnH5CEFFMbNwFKmf5xYeXKyJ',2,'text/html','',1,'Things are so different here.  People seem nicer, contrary to the general opinion in the South that everyone from the North is a dick.  I\'ve never found that, and I think its one of the reasons I wanted to go back.  I am seriously considering making the move again.  I\'ll just need to bite the bullet on that $1700 rent bill.','2018-07-30 11:57:55','2018-07-30 11:57:55'),('286','zE1CJuMdnKRzCVuwA6AKY6sBWGr3K13B',2,'text/html','',0,'I am sick and tired of North Carolina.  I ','2018-09-07 12:26:43','2018-09-07 12:26:43'),('287','zE1CJuMdnKRzCVuwA6AKY6sBWGr3K13B',2,'text/html','',1,'I should have never returned to this place.  I have always disliked it, and should have thought more carefully about my decision to come back here.','2018-09-07 12:27:17','2018-09-07 12:27:17'),('288','8vms73khI5X2NM8wrFi5huGRKQnqWOiI',2,'text/html','',0,'Highly considering moving back up North to see some new things.\n','2018-09-23 21:55:43','2018-09-23 21:55:43'),('289','7CQInwMBZB2hWEWj6fywqsMMDcZBLtEX',2,'text/html','',0,'For the past five years, I\'ve been working with SQL server in some way, shape or form.  I\'ve neve    r had to administer it, but have always had to wrangle some data out of it.  Fortunately, they\'ve     made it simple for us Linux guys to get going with it, and I have to say that I\'m impressed with     what they\'ve done.  Now, most open-source aficionados will probably want to use a product that i    s completely open-source like MariaDB or Postgres.  So why would one consider a Microsoft product     in the first place?','2018-11-21 15:44:53','2018-11-21 15:44:53'),('29','M5MZE6UVLCXEySFGtLEi0XVB22Uthw5s',2,'text/html','',1,'On most days when I\'m not doing music, you can find me programming either Javascript, Lucee or C.  To be productive in C requires a multitude of other tools--such as a compiler, debugger and a leak checker.  Often times too, you\'ll want to invoke something to make sure your program is doing what you expect.  For this reason, it should make a worthy candidate for breaking down how an advanced Vim setup would conceptually work.','2017-07-04 16:00:13','2017-07-04 16:00:13'),('290','7CQInwMBZB2hWEWj6fywqsMMDcZBLtEX',2,'text/html','',1,'First, the developer versions are free.  Second, depending on the scope of the project, the developer version can serve as a data backend for quite a while without hitting limits that would force one to upgrade to a professionally licensed version.  Third, for a Microsoft tool, the command     line interfaces and files fit right in with what I would normally be doing on any other stack, so I am not forced to use a GUI tool (or worse yet, an entire virtual machine) just to get a development setup going.','2018-11-21 15:45:38','2018-11-21 15:45:38'),('291','7CQInwMBZB2hWEWj6fywqsMMDcZBLtEX',2,'text/html','',2,'A final benefit is the fact that SQL server is the name of the game in many East Coast companies that are not startups.  While this isn\'t really an independent selling point, the fact that Microsoft has gone through some great lengths to make their product Linux-friendly is.   Apple can\'t claim this, as I still have to buy a Mac system to do <i>any</i> Cocoa/HighSierra/iOS development.  So, as a contractor, I win by being able to branch out of Linux world and build solutions for companies beholden to the Microsoft stack.  As a student or entry-level professional, I don\'t limit myself to startups (which often don\'t sport the same budget or talent as larger companies).','2018-11-21 15:46:50','2018-11-21 15:46:50'),('292','7CQInwMBZB2hWEWj6fywqsMMDcZBLtEX',2,'text/html','',3,'Now, this brings me to one negative.   My first time testing a Linux install was a little convoluted.  Following Microsoft\'s documentation worked most of the time, but some snags were hit.  Since moving to Arch primarily and using some of the well-maintained packages in the AUR, I have had a lot less trouble getting up and running.  I don\'t use Ubuntu or Fedora anymore, so I have not had the chance to run the program on either of those.   I will write another short article in the     future defining how the install process works on Arch, hopefully winning other developers over in the process.','2018-11-21 15:47:33','2018-11-21 15:47:33'),('293','yMUwxZc0y7Eg7sATSEsNZ7N0MQxF62k4',2,'text/html','',0,'Lucee (and other CFML engines) still support case-insensitivity.  For some situations this works well, but today it really isn\'t preferable.  One of CFML\'s biggest limitations is dealing with JSON.  It\'s Serialization functions return a string with uppercase keys.  This is annoying and frustrating when dealing with Javascript, which is NOT case insensitive.  If you are tasked with designing an API or SOAP resource with ColdFusion, you can use a RegEx to fix this.','2018-12-12 16:10:32','2018-12-12 16:10:32'),('294','yMUwxZc0y7Eg7sATSEsNZ7N0MQxF62k4',2,'text/html','',1,'To handle JSON serialization, CFML  takes its binary representation of your object (usually a struct) and turns into a \"stringified map\" if you will.  By default, we\'ll come out with something like the following after running SerializeJSON on some large structure.','2018-12-12 16:11:50','2018-12-12 16:11:50'),('295','yMUwxZc0y7Eg7sATSEsNZ7N0MQxF62k4',2,'text/html','',2,'<pre>\n','2018-12-12 16:12:53','2018-12-12 16:12:53'),('296','yMUwxZc0y7Eg7sATSEsNZ7N0MQxF62k4',2,'text/html','',3,'<pre>\n{\"MESSAGE\":\"Credentials invalid.\", \"HTTPSTATUS\":401, \"CALLSTATUS\":0}\n</pre>\n','2018-12-12 16:13:08','2018-12-12 16:13:08'),('297','yMUwxZc0y7Eg7sATSEsNZ7N0MQxF62k4',2,'text/html','',4,'So, now we have a string representation of what was once a binary object.  All we have to get this working with something like JS or Dart is change those uppercase key values to lowercase.  That boils to a fairly straightforward regular expression:','2018-12-12 16:14:44','2018-12-12 16:14:44'),('298','yMUwxZc0y7Eg7sATSEsNZ7N0MQxF62k4',2,'text/html','',5,'<pre>\nREReplace( a, \'\"([[:upper:]]*)\":\', \'\"\\L\\1\":\', \"ALL\" );\n</pre>','2018-12-12 16:16:06','2018-12-12 16:16:06'),('299','yMUwxZc0y7Eg7sATSEsNZ7N0MQxF62k4',2,'text/html','',6,'<pre>\n//Assume that \'a\' is a reference to the string above.\nREReplace( a, \'\"([[:upper:]]*)\":\', \'\"\\L\\1\":\', \"ALL\" );\n</pre>\n','2018-12-12 16:17:07','2018-12-12 16:17:07'),('3','8T7H7D57juXfgTmtA3VmwfXJvP7v5ADS',2,'text/html','',2,'sadfsadfdsa','2017-07-03 16:43:41','2017-07-03 16:43:41'),('30','M5MZE6UVLCXEySFGtLEi0XVB22Uthw5s',2,'text/html','',2,'<h3 class=\"inner-spirit\">Scenario #1: Invoking make from an editor window</h3>\n\n<pre>\nmap <C-m> :!clear && make\n</pre> \n\n','2017-07-04 16:01:46','2017-07-04 16:01:46'),('300','nki5QfbON3G3uNnFbNNtg45NUzAOy7Ie',2,'text/html','',0,'Lucee (and other CFML engines) were based off of the idea that case-insensitivity is a good thing.  At one point, this was probably true.  For anyone who has worked with it recently though, one of CFML\'s biggest limitations seems to be dealing with JSON. It\'s Serialization functions return a string with uppercase keys regardless of what kind of data you feed it.  For me, it caused quite a few annoying bugs when dealing with API responses in Javascript.  Fortunately, a fix is pretty easy to come by--and if you are tasked with designing an API or SOAP resource with ColdFusion, you may find this interesting.','2018-12-12 16:38:04','2018-12-12 16:38:04'),('301','nki5QfbON3G3uNnFbNNtg45NUzAOy7Ie',2,'text/html','',1,'To handle JSON serialization, CFML takes its binary representation of your object (usually a struct) and turns into a \"stringified map\" if you will. So assuming we feed it an item (<i>storeItem</i> here) following some sort of hierarchical format:','2018-12-12 16:38:32','2018-12-12 16:38:32'),('302','nki5QfbON3G3uNnFbNNtg45NUzAOy7Ie',2,'text/html','',2,'<pre>\nstoreItem = {\n	title = \"Weezy Ball\"\n 	,description = \"Fun for Dogs, Cats and bozos alike\"\n	,cost = 3.96\n	,keywords = [ \"shine\", \"on\", \"you\", \"crazy\", \"diamond\" ]\n	,colors  = {\n		white = \"0xfffff\"\n		,black = \"0x000000\"\n		,green = \"0x00ff00\"\n	}\n}\n</pre>','2018-12-12 16:38:37','2018-12-12 16:38:37'),('303','nki5QfbON3G3uNnFbNNtg45NUzAOy7Ie',2,'text/html','',3,'...we\'ll come out with something like the following after running SerializeJSON.','2018-12-12 16:38:46','2018-12-12 16:38:46'),('304','nki5QfbON3G3uNnFbNNtg45NUzAOy7Ie',2,'text/html','',4,'<pre>\n//INPUT:\nsiJson = SerializeJSON( storeItem );\nwriteoutput( siJson );\n\n//OUTPUT: (Eww, uppercase JSON keys...)\n{\"KEYWORDS\":[\"shine\",\"on\",\"you\",\"crazy\",\"diamond\"],\"COLORS\":{\"BLACK\":\"0x000000\",\"GREEN\":\"0x00ff00\",\"WHITE\":\"0xfffff\"},\"COST\":3.96,\"TITLE\":\"Weezy Ball\",\"DESCRIPTION\":\"Fun for Dogs, Cats and bozos alike\"}\n</pre>','2018-12-12 16:38:52','2018-12-12 16:38:52'),('305','nki5QfbON3G3uNnFbNNtg45NUzAOy7Ie',2,'text/html','',5,'So, now we have a string representation of what was once a binary object. This would work for all intents and purposes, but it\'s not natural to a user (I guess <i>the developer</i> in this case) and does not follow convention of any other common APIs.  We could run some kind of mapping function in Javascript to fix it too, but that would be equally cumbersome as we\'d not only have to deal with our server\'s responses, but we\'d also have to deal with response correctness on the client side.  Aggravating.','2018-12-12 16:39:01','2018-12-12 16:39:01'),('306','nki5QfbON3G3uNnFbNNtg45NUzAOy7Ie',2,'text/html','',6,'To make something a little more tasteful (and more useful out of the box with plain old Javascript or Dart) we really need to change those uppercase key values to lowercase. That boils down to a fairly straightforward regular expression.  CFML\'s regex functions return a string if the regex was found.  Otherwise, they return an unchanged copy.  So re-using our store item from above.','2018-12-12 16:39:06','2018-12-12 16:39:06'),('307','nki5QfbON3G3uNnFbNNtg45NUzAOy7Ie',2,'text/html','',7,'<pre>\n//INPUT:\nsiJson = SerializeJson( storeItem );\nsiJson = REReplace( siJson, \'\"([[:upper:]]*)\":\', \'\"\\L\\1\":\', \"ALL\" );\n\n//OUTPUT: (Ah, now that\'s something I can deal with)\n{\"keywords\":[\"shine\",\"on\",\"you\",\"crazy\",\"diamond\"],\"colors\":\n{\"black\":\"0x000000\",\n\"green\":\"0x00ff00\",\n\"white\":\"0xfffff\"},\n\"cost\":3.96,\"title\":\"Weezy Ball\",\n\"description\":\"Fun for Dogs, Cats and bozos alike\"}\n</pre>','2018-12-12 16:39:32','2018-12-12 16:39:32'),('308','nki5QfbON3G3uNnFbNNtg45NUzAOy7Ie',2,'text/html','',8,'Hope this helps others who may run into such a situation.  I was plenty annoyed on a number of occasions by this, and could not find a simple solution for it online.','2018-12-12 16:39:51','2018-12-12 16:39:51'),('309','rRHWujUiF3Guetu1kcuYILaEsvGzJ4gq',4,'image/jpeg','',0,'trmENSBdgycvFsjt23AqaL0Z3yf3GVMx.jpg','2018-12-20 15:08:22','2018-12-20 15:08:22'),('31','M5MZE6UVLCXEySFGtLEi0XVB22Uthw5s',2,'text/html','',3,'The above sequence maps the sequence Ctrl-m to commands that clear the terminal window and run Make for the primary target. Typing the code above into your .vimrc, saving the file and reopening Vim will allow you to do the same. This trivial command will find use with most C, C and probably even Rust projects. That said, notice the biggest takeaway here.  Mapping key sequences to shell commands is as easy as adding a line to a text file.  (It could be easier, but for a tool as old as Vim--this is a pretty good solution.)','2017-07-04 16:03:35','2017-07-04 16:03:35'),('310','rRHWujUiF3Guetu1kcuYILaEsvGzJ4gq',2,'text/html','',1,'oh my','2018-12-20 15:08:28','2018-12-20 15:08:28'),('311','mHCasGxLVQhR6CMg2NH2JHC5MdqWZB2e',2,'text/html','',0,'<pre>\n<html>\n<link rel=\"stylesheet\" href=\"death.css\">\n<invalidTag src=\"three.js\"></script>\n<!-- probably time to put this in a file -->\n<invalidTag>\ndocument.addEventListener(\"DOMContentLoaded\", function(evt) {\n	console.log( \"press \'q\' to start demo\" );\n	started = 0;\n\n	//Quick crude math to calculate an octave (though it\'s not tuned for Western scale)\n	for (i=1; i<13; i++ ) console.log( 440 + (( 440/12 ) * i) );\n\n	//Reference list\n	//var notes = [ 440 /*middle c*/, 476.6, 510, 550, 586.66, 623.33, 660, 696.66, 733.33, 770, 806.66, 843.33, 880, 600, 600, 600, 600  ];\n\n	//var play = { a: { freq: notes[0], ref: null },w: { freq: notes[1], ref: null },s: { freq: notes[2], ref: null },e: { freq: notes[3], ref: null },d: { freq: notes[4], ref: null },f: { freq: notes[5], ref: null },t: { freq: notes[6], ref: null },g: { freq: notes[7], ref: null },y: { freq: notes[8], ref: null },h: { freq: notes[9], ref: null },u: { freq: notes[10], ref: null },j: { freq: notes[11], ref: null },k: { freq: notes[12] /*high c*/, ref: null },o: { freq: notes[13], ref: null },l: { freq: notes[14], ref: null },p: { freq: notes[15], ref: null }, \';\': { freq: notes[16], ref: null }, \'\"\': { freq: notes[17], ref: null } };\n\n	//Eventually, this should just be a class\n	var Keys = {\n		 \'a\': { freq: 440, ref: null, gui: null, isMid: 0 }\n		,\'w\': { freq: 476, ref: null, gui: null, isMid: 1 }\n		,\'s\': { freq: 510, ref: null, gui: null, isMid: 0 }\n		,\'e\': { freq: 550, ref: null, gui: null, isMid: 1 }\n		,\'d\': { freq: 586, ref: null, gui: null, isMid: 0 }\n		,\'f\': { freq: 623, ref: null, gui: null, isMid: 0 }\n		,\'t\': { freq: 660, ref: null, gui: null, isMid: 1 }\n		,\'g\': { freq: 696, ref: null, gui: null, isMid: 0 }\n		,\'y\': { freq: 733, ref: null, gui: null, isMid: 1 }\n		,\'h\': { freq: 770, ref: null, gui: null, isMid: 0 }\n		,\'u\': { freq: 806, ref: null, gui: null, isMid: 1 }\n		,\'j\': { freq: 843, ref: null, gui: null, isMid: 0 }\n		,\'k\': { freq: 880, ref: null, gui: null, isMid: 0 }\n		,\'o\': { freq: 440, ref: null, gui: null, isMid: 0 }\n		,\'l\': { freq: 440, ref: null, gui: null, isMid: 0 }\n		,\'p\': { freq: 440, ref: null, gui: null, isMid: 0 }\n		,\';\': { freq: 440, ref: null, gui: null, isMid: 0 }\n		,\'\"\': { freq: 440, ref: null, gui: null, isMid: 0 }\n	};\n\n	//Gui should be a class too:\n	//anim: animate the key going up and down\n	//geo, mat and cube to control the mapping and position of the shape\n	function keyUpDown ( boo ) {\n		//the key should go no further than a certain point\n		//and if released early, should come up\n	console.log( this.type );\n	var drop = ( this.type ) ? -0.1 : -1; \nconsole.log( drop );\n		this.cube.position.z = ( boo ) ? drop : this.oPosition.z;\n	}\n\n	//three.js\n	var scene = new THREE.Scene();\n	scene.background = new THREE.Color( 0x0000cc );\n	var camera = new THREE.PerspectiveCamera( 75, window.innerWidth/window.innerHeight, 0.1, 1000 );\n\n	var renderer = new THREE.WebGLRenderer({ antialias: true });\n	renderer.setSize( window.innerWidth, window.innerHeight );\n	document.body.appendChild( renderer.domElement );\n	camera.position.z = 14;\n\n	//generate all the pjanoo keeeeeeis\n	var posStart = -6;\n	var keyDepth = 1.5;\n	for ( k in Keys ) {\n		var g = Keys[k].gui = { oPosition: { x: 0, y: 0, z: 0 }, anim: keyUpDown, type: Keys[k].isMid };\n		if ( g.type ) { //or just pull calc on the fly \n			g.geometry = new THREE.BoxGeometry( 1, 5, keyDepth );\n			g.material = new THREE.MeshBasicMaterial( { color: 0x000000 } );\n		}\n		else {\n			g.geometry = new THREE.BoxGeometry( 1.6, 8, keyDepth );\n			g.material = new THREE.MeshBasicMaterial( { color: 0xffffff } );\n		}\n		g.cube = new THREE.Mesh( g.geometry, g.material );\n		g.oPosition.z = g.cube.position.z = ( Keys[k].isMid ) ? 0.6 : 0;\n		g.oPosition.y = g.cube.position.y = ( Keys[k].isMid ) ? 1 : -0.5;\n		g.oPosition.x = g.cube.position.x = posStart;\n		posStart += 1.2;\n		scene.add( g.cube );\n	}\n\n	//listeners for web audio and whatnot	\n	document.addEventListener(\"keydown\", function(evt) {\n		if ( !started && evt.key == \'q\' ) {\n			console.log( \'audioctx started...\' );\n			var aCtx = new (window.AudioContext || window.webKitAudioContext)();\n\n			//Record sounds	\n			document.getElementById(\'rec\').addEventListener(\"click\", function(evt) {\n				evt.preventDefault();\n				//record whatever is played back\n			});\n\n			//Play and pause sounds\n			document.addEventListener(\"keydown\", function(evt) {\n				if ( \'awsedftgyhujkolp;\"\'.indexOf( evt.key ) > -1 ) {\n					console.log( \'play\' );	\n					var oNode = Keys[ evt.key ];\n					if ( !oNode.ref ) {\n						oNode.ref = aCtx.createOscillator();\n						oNode.ref.type = \'sawtooth\';\n						oNode.ref.frequency.setValueAtTime( oNode.freq, aCtx.currentTime ); \n						oNode.ref.connect( aCtx.destination );\n						oNode.gui.anim( 1 );\n						oNode.ref.start();\n					}\n				}\n			});\n\n			document.addEventListener(\"keyup\", function(evt) {\n				if ( \'awsedftgyhujkolp;\"\'.indexOf( evt.key ) > -1 ) {\n					console.log( \'stop\' );	\n					var oNode = Keys[ evt.key ];\n					oNode.gui.anim( 0 );\n					oNode.ref.stop();\n					oNode.ref = null;\n				}\n			});	\n		}\n	});\n\n\n	//might make more sense to trigger animations from elsewhere...\n	var animate = function () {\n		requestAnimationFrame( animate );\n		//cube.rotation.x += 0.01;\n		//cube.rotation.y += 0.01;\n		renderer.render( scene, camera );\n	};\n\n	animate();\n});\n</script>\n\n\n<body>\n\n	<!--- three.js can make a keyboard ---><!--- really should control this with canvas --->\n\n	<!--- this menu controls other things --->	\n	<div class=menu>\n		<div class=ctrl id=rec></div>\n		<div class=ctrl id=stop></div>\n		<div class=ctrl id=play></div>\n	</div>\n\n	<!--- this menu controls mixer elements --->	\n	<div class=mixer>\n		<div class=sCtrl></div>	\n		<div class=sCtrl></div>	\n		<div class=sCtrl></div>	\n		<div class=sCtrl></div>	\n		<div class=sCtrl></div>	\n		<div class=sCtrl></div>	\n		<div class=sCtrl></div>	\n		<div class=sCtrl></div>	\n		<div class=sCtrl></div>	\n		<div class=sCtrl></div>	\n		<div class=sCtrl></div>	\n		<div class=sCtrl></div>	\n	</div>\n\n</body>\n</html>\n</pre>','2018-12-20 15:15:48','2018-12-20 15:15:48'),('312','mHCasGxLVQhR6CMg2NH2JHC5MdqWZB2e',2,'text/html','',1,'code and stuff...','2018-12-20 15:15:57','2018-12-20 15:15:57'),('313','cUlybhs7Y7xoknQL5NSM5rKqWiCsWY0e',2,'text/html','',0,'asdfsadfasd','2019-01-27 00:27:44','2019-01-27 00:27:44'),('314','cUlybhs7Y7xoknQL5NSM5rKqWiCsWY0e',2,'text/html','',1,'asdfsad','2019-01-27 00:27:44','2019-01-27 00:27:44'),('315','6iv16OaudF2InEBd16oV5LjeeRGz3ZMY',2,'text/html','',0,'Why do we move?  Why do we do what we do?','2019-06-10 15:05:16','2019-06-10 15:05:16'),('32','M5MZE6UVLCXEySFGtLEi0XVB22Uthw5s',2,'text/html','',4,'If we prefix the \'map\' command with: au Filetype $file where $file is the full name of a file type (not its extension), then we\'ll be able to \"filter\" that command to only run on the matching file types. I\'ll illustrate with another example below.','2017-07-04 16:03:51','2017-07-04 16:03:51'),('33','M5MZE6UVLCXEySFGtLEi0XVB22Uthw5s',2,'text/html','',5,'<h3 class=\"inner-spirit\">Scenario #2 - Invoke make on C files only</h3>','2017-07-04 16:04:08','2017-07-04 16:04:08'),('34','M5MZE6UVLCXEySFGtLEi0XVB22Uthw5s',2,'text/html','',6,'Now let\'s say that I\'m a PHP programmer that likes to optimize and constantly finds himself switching between C for low-level speedy work and PHP for pretty flitzy string-related things. We can do the following to map targets to certain file types.','2017-07-04 16:04:13','2017-07-04 16:04:13'),('35','M5MZE6UVLCXEySFGtLEi0XVB22Uthw5s',2,'text/html','',7,'<pre>\nau Filetype c map :!clear && make au Filetype php map :!php -S localhost:2888\n</pre>','2017-07-04 16:04:37','2017-07-04 16:04:37'),('36','M5MZE6UVLCXEySFGtLEi0XVB22Uthw5s',2,'text/html','',8,'Now every time I hit Ctrl-m when working with a C file, vim will run the default target using the Makefile in my current directory. The same sequence in PHP will start a local server.','2017-07-04 16:04:50','2017-07-04 16:04:50'),('37','z3JCilzgFmTvsDwj3mZxTKqEW0ukG4t0',2,'text/html','',0,'DWM is a lightweight tiling window manager from the guys at <a href=\"http://suckless.org\">suckless.org</a>. I would have given up Linux if it weren\'t for this program and the ability to handle life through a web browser. It\'s easy to build (on a modern system with a few dependencies) and easy to install. There is a tutorial on the project\'s homepage, but over time I\'ve stumbled upon a lot of \"special\" features that aren\'t covered there. The biggest of these is multi-monitor support. It seems to just work provided Xinerama is available on the target system.  Even if it\'s not, XRandR handles the job just as well. Like Vim and other \"arcane\" Unix tools, controlling DWM takes some getting used to.  Follow the rabbit hole and see a quick guide to running it on your system and trying it out.','2017-07-04 16:58:43','2017-07-04 16:58:43'),('38','z3JCilzgFmTvsDwj3mZxTKqEW0ukG4t0',2,'text/html','',1,'<p>These first few commands are base commands that work regardless of how many monitors you\'re using</p>\n<ul>\n\n<li>\nShift   Mod   q\n<ul><li>\nQuits dwm and takes you to a terminal\n</li></ul>\n</li>\n\n<li>\nMod   j\n<ul><li>\nCycles \"left\" between all windows in a workspace\n(\"right\" is in quotes because it could also mean down)\n</li></ul>\n</li>\n\n<li>\nMod   k\n<ul><li>\nCycles \"right\" between all windows in a workspace\n(\"right\" is in quotes because it could also mean down)\n</li></ul>\n</li>\n\n<li>\nMod   m\n<ul><li>\nSwitches to \"monocle\" mode (which, in essence, makes the current window full screen)\n</li></ul>\n</li>\n\n<li>\nMod   t\n<ul><li>\nSwitches to \'tiled\' mode.  All current windows will fit into the current workspace and new windows will fit in line.\n</li></ul>\n</li>\n\n<li>\nMod   f\n<ul><li>\nSwitches to \'floating\' mode.  Windows don\'t snap, and just kind of \"float\".   Like clouds...  \n</li></ul>\n</li>\n</ul>','2017-07-04 16:59:25','2017-07-04 16:59:25'),('39','z3JCilzgFmTvsDwj3mZxTKqEW0ukG4t0',2,'text/html','',2,'<p>\nThese commands are only useful with multi monitor setups:\n<ul>\n\n<li>\nShift   Mod   &lt;\n<ul><li>\nMoves a window to the right of the current workspace\n</li></ul>\n</li>\n\n<li>\nShift   Mod   &gt;\n<ul><li>\nMoves a window to the left of the current workspace\n</li></ul>\n</li>\n\n<li>\nMod   &lt;\n<ul><li>\nSelects the workspace to the right of the current one</li></ul>\n</li>\n\n<li>\nMod   &gt;\n<ul><li>\nSelects the workspace to the left of the current one\n</li></ul>\n</li>\n</ul>\n\n</p>\n','2017-07-04 17:01:54','2017-07-04 17:01:54'),('4','8T7H7D57juXfgTmtA3VmwfXJvP7v5ADS',2,'text/html','',3,'dsafdsafadsfadsfdsafdsafdsafdsafdsafdsa','2017-07-03 16:43:44','2017-07-03 16:43:44'),('40','z3JCilzgFmTvsDwj3mZxTKqEW0ukG4t0',2,'text/html','',3,'Now DWM is not suckless.org\'s only good Unix tool.  I also depend on st whenever I am working on any kind of Linux.  Even though it is very bare bones, it seems to be only terminal that I can just get up and go in.  It includes zooming and does not require a lot of craziness to configure.   I think the two tools covered here go hand in hand--but, my dear reader,  you\'ll have to download them, give them a shot and be the judge of that.','2017-07-04 17:04:37','2017-07-04 17:04:37'),('42','zRMJTMlET3v8cRHTDLGg3WYTC0CSO2Rw',2,'text/html','',0,'For the last 2 months, I\'ve been working hard on a blogging tool to make it a bit easier to create a standard, nice looking (and free) website. It is built on top of both Lucee, a free and open-source variant of this thing called <a href=\"http://www.adobe.com/products/coldfusion-family.html\">ColdFusion</a>; and a simplistic MVC framework called <a href=\"http://ramar.filbert.com/coldmvc\">ColdMVC</a>. So far, it\'s not a big pain to use or setup. The glitzy parts (like CSS3 transitions and rollover effects) are turning out to be the most intensive coding to do. I guess the more neurotic of a designer you are, the more time you\'ll spend tweaking these sorts of details. There will be more to be said here, so watch this space.','2017-07-11 19:23:18','2017-07-11 19:23:18'),('43','73UU22z1QglINMMVyREOtR1NVzS7xoeM',2,'text/html','',0,'I run into trouble with this concept when dealing with slideshow libraries. I try not to use Bootstrap either. This might just be a laziness thing, but I would rather have a good idea of how things work then have to rely on a framework to do it all for me. I really like that level of control.','2017-07-11 19:24:04','2017-07-11 19:24:04'),('44','73UU22z1QglINMMVyREOtR1NVzS7xoeM',2,'text/html','',1,'To see how this worked I whipped up a web page with 5 separate divs. Each stretch to be 100% wide, but use a different height to demonstrate the effects of different aspect ratios.','2017-07-11 19:24:08','2017-07-11 19:24:08'),('45','73UU22z1QglINMMVyREOtR1NVzS7xoeM',2,'text/html','',2,'The CSS to set this up these five divs is below. As far as I know, no resetting is needed to get this to render correctly.','2017-07-11 19:24:13','2017-07-11 19:24:13'),('46','73UU22z1QglINMMVyREOtR1NVzS7xoeM',2,'text/html','',3,'<pre>\n.asp, .aspect1-1 {\n    background-color: red;\n    width: 100%;\n    padding-top: 100%; /* 1:1 Aspect Ratio */\n    position: relative; /* If you want text inside of it */\n    background-image: url( \"aspectRatios2.png\" );\n    background-size: 100% 100%;\n    margin-bottom: 10%;\n}\n\n.aspect3-2 {\n    background-color: red;\n  padding-top: 66.66%;\n}\n\n.aspect4-3 {\n    background-color: red;\n  padding-top: 75%;\n}\n\n.aspect8-5 {\n    background-color: #ffffb3;\n  padding-top: 56.25%;\n}\n\n.aspect16-9 {\n    background-color: #aaaaaa;\n  padding-top: 56.25%;\n}\n\n\n/* If you want text inside of the container */\n.text {\n    position: absolute;\n    top: 0;\n    left: 0;\n    bottom: 0;\n    right: 0;\n}\n\n#container {\n  position: relative;\n  width: 792px;\n  margin-left: -396px;\n  left: 50%;\n}\n</pre>','2017-07-11 19:24:25','2017-07-11 19:24:25'),('47','73UU22z1QglINMMVyREOtR1NVzS7xoeM',2,'text/html','',4,'Now for the HTML.','2017-07-11 19:24:30','2017-07-11 19:24:30'),('48','73UU22z1QglINMMVyREOtR1NVzS7xoeM',2,'text/html','',5,'<pre>\n<body>\n  <div id=container>\n    <div class=\"asp aspect1-1\">\n    </div>\n\n    <div class=\"asp aspect3-2\">\n    </div>\n\n    <div class=\"asp aspect4-3\">\n    </div>\n\n    <div class=\"asp aspect8-5\">\n    </div>\n\n    <div class=\"asp aspect16-9\">\n    </div>\n  </div>\n</body>\n</pre>','2017-07-11 19:24:41','2017-07-11 19:24:41'),('49','73UU22z1QglINMMVyREOtR1NVzS7xoeM',2,'text/html','',6,'I tied this all together with a <a href=\"https://codepen.io/ancollins/pen/aWvQmq\">codepen</a>. So if you\'re willing to keep some code like this around, you now have access to a tool that can help you deal with wild image sizes.','2017-07-11 19:25:34','2017-07-11 19:25:34'),('5','6ohgjOkBaqAabXkZHwmSUbQbfFrRhwXu',2,'text/html','',0,'sadfdsaf','2017-07-03 17:02:43','2017-07-03 17:02:43'),('50','kFEBRi5lCSElQKCKC65ORRn2d8HiRFXu',2,'text/html','',0,'I run into trouble with this concept when dealing with slideshow libraries. I try not to use Bootstrap either. This might just be a laziness thing, but I would rather have a good idea of how things work then have to rely on a framework to do it all for me. I really like that level of control.','2017-07-11 19:27:00','2017-07-11 19:27:00'),('51','kFEBRi5lCSElQKCKC65ORRn2d8HiRFXu',2,'text/html','',1,'To see how this worked I whipped up a web page with 5 separate divs. Each stretch to be 100% wide, but use a different height to demonstrate the effects of different aspect ratios.','2017-07-11 19:27:03','2017-07-11 19:27:03'),('52','kFEBRi5lCSElQKCKC65ORRn2d8HiRFXu',2,'text/html','',2,'The CSS to set this up these five divs is below. As far as I know, no resetting is needed to get this to render correctly.','2017-07-11 19:27:08','2017-07-11 19:27:08'),('53','kFEBRi5lCSElQKCKC65ORRn2d8HiRFXu',2,'text/html','',3,'.asp, .aspect1-1 {\n    background-color: red;\n    width: 100%;\n    padding-top: 100%; /* 1:1 Aspect Ratio */\n    position: relative; /* If you want text inside of it */\n    background-image: url( \"aspectRatios2.png\" );\n    background-size: 100% 100%;\n    margin-bottom: 10%;\n}\n\n.aspect3-2 {\n    background-color: red;\n  padding-top: 66.66%;\n}\n\n.aspect4-3 {\n    background-color: red;\n  padding-top: 75%;\n}\n\n.aspect8-5 {\n    background-color: #ffffb3;\n  padding-top: 56.25%;\n}\n\n.aspect16-9 {\n    background-color: #aaaaaa;\n  padding-top: 56.25%;\n}\n\n\n/* If you want text inside of the container */\n.text {\n    position: absolute;\n    top: 0;\n    left: 0;\n    bottom: 0;\n    right: 0;\n}\n\n#container {\n  position: relative;\n  width: 792px;\n  margin-left: -396px;\n  left: 50%;\n}','2017-07-11 19:27:13','2017-07-11 19:27:13'),('54','FuZBzkn7vctxnDwsVv7MiqLxR4z3MKmf',2,'text/html','',0,'I run into trouble with this concept when dealing with slideshow libraries. I try not to use Bootstrap either. This might just be a laziness thing, but I would rather have a good idea of how things work then have to rely on a framework to do it all for me. I really like that level of control.','2017-07-11 19:27:31','2017-07-11 19:27:31'),('55','FuZBzkn7vctxnDwsVv7MiqLxR4z3MKmf',2,'text/html','',1,'To see how this worked I whipped up a web page with 5 separate divs. Each stretch to be 100% wide, but use a different height to demonstrate the effects of different aspect ratios.','2017-07-11 19:27:34','2017-07-11 19:27:34'),('56','FuZBzkn7vctxnDwsVv7MiqLxR4z3MKmf',2,'text/html','',2,'The CSS to set this up these five divs is below. As far as I know, no resetting is needed to get this to render correctly.','2017-07-11 19:27:37','201