p aspect3-2\"&gt;\n    &lt;/div&gt;\n\n    &lt;div class=\"asp aspect4-3\"&gt;\n    &lt;/div&gt;\n\n    &lt;div class=\"asp aspect8-5\"&gt;\n    &lt;/div&gt;\n\n    &lt;div class=\"asp aspect16-9\"&gt;\n    &lt;/div&gt;\n  &lt;/div&gt;\n&lt;/body&gt;','2017-07-11 19:29:16','2017-07-11 19:29:16'),('67','LMhYsyzd68asvhTI0vef1IKGnXaz2cWv',2,'text/html','',6,'I tied this all together with a <a href=\"https://codepen.io/ancollins/pen/aWvQmq\">codepen</a>. So if you\'re willing to keep some code like this around, you now have access to a tool that can help you deal with wild image sizes.','2017-07-11 19:29:30','2017-07-11 19:29:30'),('68','RGYL2sDeOL5RxjbwTVF3BIDfmLK2TDVK',2,'text/html','',0,'I run into trouble with this concept when dealing with slideshow libraries. I try not to use Bootstrap either. This might just be a laziness thing, but I would rather have a good idea of how things work then have to rely on a framework to do it all for me. I really like that level of control.','2017-07-11 19:30:04','2017-07-11 19:30:04'),('69','RGYL2sDeOL5RxjbwTVF3BIDfmLK2TDVK',2,'text/html','',1,'To see how this worked I whipped up a web page with 5 separate divs. Each stretch to be 100% wide, but use a different height to demonstrate the effects of different aspect ratios.','2017-07-11 19:30:07','2017-07-11 19:30:07'),('7','6ohgjOkBaqAabXkZHwmSUbQbfFrRhwXu',4,'image/jpeg','',2,'azaLeVaE2l64DIWcqYmdtsYqXxHrgkAV.jpg','2017-07-03 17:02:49','2017-07-03 17:02:49'),('70','RGYL2sDeOL5RxjbwTVF3BIDfmLK2TDVK',2,'text/html','',2,'The CSS to set this up these five divs is below. As far as I know, no resetting is needed to get this to render correctly.','2017-07-11 19:30:11','2017-07-11 19:30:11'),('71','RGYL2sDeOL5RxjbwTVF3BIDfmLK2TDVK',2,'text/html','',3,'<pre>\n.asp, .aspect1-1 {\n    background-color: red;\n    width: 100%;\n    padding-top: 100%; /* 1:1 Aspect Ratio */\n    position: relative; /* If you want text inside of it */\n    background-image: url( \"aspectRatios2.png\" );\n    background-size: 100% 100%;\n    margin-bottom: 10%;\n}\n\n.aspect3-2 {\n    background-color: red;\n  padding-top: 66.66%;\n}\n\n.aspect4-3 {\n    background-color: red;\n  padding-top: 75%;\n}\n\n.aspect8-5 {\n    background-color: #ffffb3;\n  padding-top: 56.25%;\n}\n\n.aspect16-9 {\n    background-color: #aaaaaa;\n  padding-top: 56.25%;\n}\n\n\n/* If you want text inside of the container */\n.text {\n    position: absolute;\n    top: 0;\n    left: 0;\n    bottom: 0;\n    right: 0;\n}\n\n#container {\n  position: relative;\n  width: 792px;\n  margin-left: -396px;\n  left: 50%;\n}\n</pre>','2017-07-11 19:30:21','2017-07-11 19:30:21'),('72','RGYL2sDeOL5RxjbwTVF3BIDfmLK2TDVK',2,'text/html','',4,'Now for the HTML.','2017-07-11 19:30:27','2017-07-11 19:30:27'),('73','RGYL2sDeOL5RxjbwTVF3BIDfmLK2TDVK',2,'text/html','',5,'<pre>\n&lt;body&gt;\n  &lt;div id=container&gt;\n    &lt;div class=\"asp aspect1-1\"&gt;\n    &lt;/div&gt;\n\n    &lt;div class=\"asp aspect3-2\"&gt;\n    &lt;/div&gt;\n\n    &lt;div class=\"asp aspect4-3\"&gt;\n    &lt;/div&gt;\n\n    &lt;div class=\"asp aspect8-5\"&gt;\n    &lt;/div&gt;\n\n    &lt;div class=\"asp aspect16-9\"&gt;\n    &lt;/div&gt;\n  &lt;/div&gt;\n&lt;/body&gt;\n</pre>','2017-07-11 19:30:37','2017-07-11 19:30:37'),('74','RGYL2sDeOL5RxjbwTVF3BIDfmLK2TDVK',2,'text/html','',6,'I tied this all together with a <a href=\"https://codepen.io/ancollins/pen/aWvQmq\">codepen</a>. So if you\'re willing to keep some code like this around, you now have access to a tool that can help you deal with wild image sizes.','2017-07-11 19:30:49','2017-07-11 19:30:49'),('75','oxN3WdX8e5woq1c1x58Y6ixABlzE7ij5',2,'text/html','',0,'Unix and Windows still don\'t get along very well. I don\'t know why this is in 2017, but it\'s very much a thing. From access control lists to setting up git and mercurial, moving sound programming tools to Windows is still absolutely too difficult.','2017-07-11 19:32:53','2017-07-11 19:32:53'),('76','oxN3WdX8e5woq1c1x58Y6ixABlzE7ij5',2,'text/html','',1,'Case in point, Git for Windows (or Git in general?) has issues digesting files with Windows line endings. Mind you, this version of Git is running on a Windows system! How is that an issue?!','2017-07-11 19:32:55','2017-07-11 19:32:55'),('77','oxN3WdX8e5woq1c1x58Y6ixABlzE7ij5',2,'text/html','',2,'I discovered this nonsense when playing around with writing some hooks. It\'s an incredibly simple hook, but it never came together. It was working fine on Cygwin and regular *nix, as well. Below is the example, borrowed from this <a href=\"https://www.digitalocean.com/community/tutorials/how-to-use-git-hooks-to-automate-development-and-deployment-tasks\">page</a> via Digital Ocean:','2017-07-11 19:33:41','2017-07-11 19:33:41'),('78','oxN3WdX8e5woq1c1x58Y6ixABlzE7ij5',2,'text/html','',3,'<pre>\n#Adapted from the Git manual.   This only allows pushes of the master branch.\nwhile oldrev newrev ref\ndo\n     if [[ $ref ~= *./master$ ]]\n     then\n         echo \"Accepting master ref...\"\n         git --work-tree=../my-dir --git-dir=. checkout -f\n     fi\ndone\n</pre>','2017-07-11 19:33:53','2017-07-11 19:33:53'),('79','oxN3WdX8e5woq1c1x58Y6ixABlzE7ij5',2,'text/html','',4,'This worked in about two minutes on Cygwin, which is a bit of a nightmare in practice, but that\'s another story. When trying to duplicate the same thing on Windows Server, error after error kept occurring. Mostly just Bash syntax errors (even though it was valid shell code). So I think maybe Git is calling up the the wrong interpreter or perhaps the while loop is a bad idea.','2017-07-11 19:33:59','2017-07-11 19:33:59'),('8','6ohgjOkBaqAabXkZHwmSUbQbfFrRhwXu',2,'text/html','',3,'safdsadf','2017-07-03 17:02:51','2017-07-03 17:02:51'),('80','oxN3WdX8e5woq1c1x58Y6ixABlzE7ij5',2,'text/html','',5,'<pre>\n#One line.  That\'s it... \ngit --work-tree=../mydir --git-dir=. checkout -f\n</pre>\n','2017-07-11 19:34:07','2017-07-11 19:34:07'),('81','oxN3WdX8e5woq1c1x58Y6ixABlzE7ij5',2,'text/html','',6,'Unfortunately, that didn\'t quite work either. Now the error was something like:','2017-07-11 19:34:12','2017-07-11 19:34:12'),('82','oxN3WdX8e5woq1c1x58Y6ixABlzE7ij5',2,'text/html','',7,'<pre>\nremote: \': not a valid identifier git\n....\n</pre>','2017-07-11 19:34:23','2017-07-11 19:34:23'),('83','oxN3WdX8e5woq1c1x58Y6ixABlzE7ij5',2,'text/html','',8,'Now that is a particularly cryptic error and that forced to start some brute force testing. I whipped up a quick script and tried some new things.','2017-07-11 19:34:28','2017-07-11 19:34:28'),('84','oxN3WdX8e5woq1c1x58Y6ixABlzE7ij5',2,'text/html','',9,'<pre>\n#adds some garbage to a file, commits and pushes to master\necho \"yah\" >> file && git add file && git commit -m \"...\" && git push\n</pre>\n','2017-07-11 19:34:37','2017-07-11 19:34:37'),('85','oxN3WdX8e5woq1c1x58Y6ixABlzE7ij5',2,'text/html','',10,'After many runs of this, it still fails.','2017-07-11 19:34:52','2017-07-11 19:34:52'),('86','oxN3WdX8e5woq1c1x58Y6ixABlzE7ij5',2,'text/html','',11,'Then it dawned on me when I saw the way that Vim saved files. DOS line endings are the default when using a Windows shell (even though Vim is running in said shell.) I opened the file in another application and saved it with Unix line endings. The hook now works. I can\'t help but wonder why so much time had to be wasted on such a trival problem. Is Git or Git for Windows really so crippled that it can\'t discern between these two? Is Git Bash the issue? Why?','2017-07-11 19:35:00','2017-07-11 19:35:00'),('87','8EVYByX5W7B6syCHj8IqDQE6xWzHyRT0',2,'text/html','',0,'I love VIM, but admittedly, it\'s not a batteries included IDE. Depending on your point of view, this is a plus or a minus. With some ingenuity, Vim can be made to act like just about any other IDE worth its salt.','2017-07-11 19:36:18','2017-07-11 19:36:18'),('88','8EVYByX5W7B6syCHj8IqDQE6xWzHyRT0',2,'text/html','',1,'A few years ago, I ran into this problem with Vim, but stumbled across Aric Blumer\'s Project plugin. It worked well, but there were a few issues I encountered:','2017-07-11 19:36:21','2017-07-11 19:36:21'),('89','8EVYByX5W7B6syCHj8IqDQE6xWzHyRT0',2,'text/html','',2,'Recreating directories is a time-consuming process To generate a list, you must type \'/C\' and specify a directory name and any files to exclude. (I got tired of this by the third time.)','2017-07-11 19:36:24','2017-07-11 19:36:24'),('9','nUKeAeU6xiwFCMtNMr58JoqtEyFgUMie',2,'text/html','',0,'sadfsdaf','2017-07-03 17:04:30','2017-07-03 17:04:30'),('90','8EVYByX5W7B6syCHj8IqDQE6xWzHyRT0',2,'text/html','',3,'Development has most probably stalled. The last version of this plugin was from October 2006 I always have to reinstall this plugin to Vim\'s setup directory on whatever system I\'m working on. However, I still really like using this plugin. It is intuitive and robust. Crashes and lockups are rare. While the \'\\c\' command (or \'\\C\' command for directories) can be slow with a large amount of files, it is extremely convenient when the top level directory changes. And once it\'s installed, it\'s finished. I don\'t have to maintain anything or worry about performance suffering just to update a few files. File system watchers seem to have these sorts of issues all the time. It may not be the software, but I just don\'t have time to debug issues like this in the middle of projects.','2017-07-11 19:36:28','2017-07-11 19:36:28'),('91','8EVYByX5W7B6syCHj8IqDQE6xWzHyRT0',2,'text/html','',4,'I\'ve come up with some workarounds for the Project plugin. I use a script called \'stree\' to quickly generate a list of files in a directory. (Please see ??? for more information.) It is nothing special. It runs a quick `find` on the directory you want to index, sorts it as best as it can by directories and files, and creates a file structured to fit with Mr. Blumer\'s plugin.','2017-07-11 19:36:32','2017-07-11 19:36:32'),('92','8EVYByX5W7B6syCHj8IqDQE6xWzHyRT0',2,'text/html','',5,'Problem solved, right? Not exactly. While fine for personal projects and slow computers. Building the index once can take a while on some systems, especially when running on an emulator such as Cygwin since Windows has no fork() call. so having a persistent file isn\'t so bad.) It\'s not great when trying to collaborate with others. Not everyone uses vim, and some places don\'t even have source control handy. So we can work around this by creating a temporary file with the same information.','2017-07-11 19:36:36','2017-07-11 19:36:36'),('93','8EVYByX5W7B6syCHj8IqDQE6xWzHyRT0',2,'text/html','',6,'<pre>\nHASH=\"/tmp/`pwd | md5sum | sed \'s/  -//\'`\"\n[ ! -f $HASH ] && $HOME/prj/te-ide/tools/stree.sh -a $HASH\nvim -c \"Project $HASH\"\n</pre>','2017-07-11 19:36:46','2017-07-11 19:36:46'),('94','8EVYByX5W7B6syCHj8IqDQE6xWzHyRT0',2,'text/html','',7,'Surely it isn\'t the most well structured script. But this is perfect to mash into your .bashrc. I called it miv(). If you want to use it yourself, wrap it in a function and call it a day.','2017-07-11 19:36:49','2017-07-11 19:36:49'),('95','8EVYByX5W7B6syCHj8IqDQE6xWzHyRT0',2,'text/html','',8,'<pre>\nfunction miv() {\n   HASH=\"/tmp/`pwd | md5sum | sed \'s/  -//\'`\"\n   [ ! -f $HASH ] && $HOME/prj/te-ide/tools/stree.sh -a $HASH\n   vim -c \"Project $HASH\"\n}\n</pre>','2017-07-11 19:37:08','2017-07-11 19:37:08'),('96','noCdsY2tCaS7emKNXC2z4ZW3RhwUnxJl',2,'text/html','',0,'Hello to you all.   In case you have been following my site and notice a new look, I am in the process of porting my portfolio to a new location.   I have a totally different, self-written blogging system running the backend of this site now.   However, I\'m still working on porting some of my old data over.  Dates may be wrong, and some things may be just plain missing.  Please pay no attention to the man behind the curtain ;).','2017-07-12 20:57:13','2017-07-12 20:57:13'),('97','q5hwffaN7f723J6Di76RLXxfTKTmoXCG',2,'text/html','',0,'I\'m starting to get more questions on what I consider to be basic AJAX usage.   \nSo, to make sure that I\'m explaining it correctly and so that others who aren\'t really familiar with it understand it, I\'ve penned a small guide to getting it working on your own websites.\nI also have done without jQuery or any other helper Javascript libraries.  \nOne reason is because the browser implementors have done a pretty good job of making an interface that makes sense.\nAnother is because I don\'t believe we should have to rely on libraries to get this pretty fundamental thing done.','2017-07-25 20:43:33','2017-07-25 20:43:33'),('98','HMRaJz3US3FKMWUer42TB28fjveN6wFX',2,'text/html','',0,'I\'m starting to get more questions on what I consider to be basic AJAX usage.   \nSo, to make sure that I\'m explaining it correctly and so that others who aren\'t really familiar with it understand it, I\'ve penned a small guide to getting it working in your own applications.\nTo better illustrate it, I\'ll avoid jQuery or any of the other popular Javascript libraries and focus on what actually happens.\n','2017-07-25 20:55:10','2017-07-25 20:55:10'),('99','HMRaJz3US3FKMWUer42TB28fjveN6wFX',2,'text/html','',1,'At its simplest, there are just four calls to make a basic AJAX implementation work. \nThe usage goes something like this:\n<pre>\nvar xhttp = new XMLHttpRequest();\nxhttp.open( “GET”, “http://somebody.com/file_from_server.txt”, false );\nxhttp.send();\nconsole.log( xhttp.responseText );\n</pre>\n','2017-07-25 20:55:18','2017-07-25 20:55:18');
